var Global_PensionRules = [

    ['CCS Pension Rules, 2021, are formulated under proviso to __________ and clause (5) of ___________ of the Constitution ','Article 309, Article 149','Article 307, Article 148','Article 309, Article 148','Article 308, Article 150','Article 309, Article 148','The President has made the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, in exercise of the powers conferred by the proviso to article 309 and clause (5) of article 148 of the Constitution and after consultation with the Comptroller and Auditor-General of India in relation to persons serving in the Indian Audit and Accounts Department. '],
['The CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, have come into force with effect from ______________','20th November, 2021','21st November, 2021','20th December, 2021','21st December, 2021','20th December, 2021','-'],
['Which of the following are not covered by the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021?','Members of the All India Services','Persons locally recruited for service in diplomatic, consular or other Indian establishments in foreign countries','Persons employed on contract except when the contract provides otherwise','All of the above','All of the above','CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, apply to government servants appointed before December 31, 2003, who are on pensionable establishments, except for railway servants, casual and daily rated employees, persons paid from contingencies, those entitled to a Contributory Provident Fund, members of the All India Services, locally recruited personnel for foreign Indian establishments, persons employed on contracts (unless the contract specifies otherwise), and those whose terms of service are governed by the Constitution or other laws.'],
['Which of the following are not covered by the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021?','railway servants','persons in casual and daily rated employment','persons paid from contingencies','All of the above','All of the above','CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, apply to government servants appointed before December 31, 2003, who are on pensionable establishments, except for railway servants, casual and daily rated employees, persons paid from contingencies, those entitled to a Contributory Provident Fund, members of the All India Services, locally recruited personnel for foreign Indian establishments, persons employed on contracts (unless the contract specifies otherwise), and those whose terms of service are governed by the Constitution or other laws.'],
['Which of the following are covered by the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021? \n1. Civilian government servants in Defense Services who are appointed substantively to civil services and posts in connection with the affairs of the Union that are on pensionable establishments. \n2. Persons entitled to the benefit of a Contributory Provident Fund. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, apply to the Government servants appointed on or before 31st day of December, 2003, including civilian Government servants in the Defence Services, appointed substantively to civil services and posts in connection with the affairs of the Union which are borne on pensionable establishments, except for railway servants, casual and daily rated employees, persons paid from contingencies, those entitled to a Contributory Provident Fund, members of the All India Services, locally recruited personnel for foreign Indian establishments, persons employed on contracts (unless the contract specifies otherwise), and those whose terms of service are governed by the Constitution or other laws.'],
['A Government servant who underwent induction training on or before December 31, 2003 and was appointed to a regular position after that date will be covered under CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, provided that:','completion of the training was required for the regular appointment','the servant received a salary or stipend during the training period','training period is also considered as qualifying service in accordance with the provisions of the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 2: These rules shall also apply to,- (1) a Government servant who was put on induction training on or before 31st day of December, 2003 followed by appointment on regular basis after 31st day of December, 2003: Provided that completion of the induction training was an essential condition for appointment on regular basis to the post, the Government servant was eligible for a salary or a stipend during the period of such training and the period of training was eligible for being counted as qualifying service in accordance with the provisions of Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972.'],
['Which of the following categories of government employees will the CCS Pension Rules apply to?',' Those who were appointed after December 31, 2003, in a Central Government department with a pension scheme other than the CCS (Pension) Rules.','Those who were appointed after December 31, 2003, in a state or autonomous body with a non-contributory pension scheme similar to the CCS (Pension) Rules.','Those who were appointed before December 31, 2003, in a state or autonomous body with a non-contributory pension scheme similar to the CCS (Pension) Rules and later appointed to a Central Government establishment to which these rules apply.','None of the above','Those who were appointed before December 31, 2003, in a state or autonomous body with a non-contributory pension scheme similar to the CCS (Pension) Rules and later appointed to a Central Government establishment to which these rules apply.','Rule 2(2): The CCS Pension Rules will be applicable to government servants who were first appointed before December 31, 2003 in a Central Government department where the employees were covered by a pension scheme other than the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, or in a State Government or an autonomous body under the Central Government or State Government with a non-contributory pension scheme similar to the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, and subsequently appointed after December 31, 2003, in a Central Government department to which these rules apply, provided that they meet all the other conditions for counting the service they rendered in the previous establishment in accordance with these rules or any general or special order issued in this regard.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding the benefits under the CCS Pension Rules for government servants appointed in temporary capacity before December 31, 2003 and retired before being appointed in substantive capacity?','The benefits under the CCS Pension Rules will not be payable to such government servants.','The benefits under the CCS Pension Rules will be payable in full to such government servants.','The benefits under the CCS Pension Rules will be payable to the extent provided in the Central Civil Services (Temporary Service) Rules, 1965, to such government servants.','The benefits under the CCS Pension Rules will be payable only if such government servants were appointed in a substantive capacity before their retirement.','The benefits under the CCS Pension Rules will be payable to the extent provided in the Central Civil Services (Temporary Service) Rules, 1965, to such government servants.','Rule 2(6): These rules shall also apply to the case of Government servants appointed in temporary capacity to civil services and posts in connection with the affairs of the Union on or before 31st day of December, 2003, who retired or were retired before having been appointed in a substantive capacity, the benefits under these rules shall be payable to the Government servant to the extent provided in the Central Civil Services (Temporary Service) Rules, 1965.'],
['Which of the following is true about the applicability of CCS (Pension) Rules to individuals who were granted temporary status?','The rules apply only if the individual was granted temporary status after December 31, 2003 with subsequent regular appointment in Government service without any break.','The rules apply only if the individual was granted temporary status before December 31, 2003 with subsequent regular appointment in Government service without any break.','The rules apply only if the individual was granted temporary status under the "Casual Labourers (Grant of Temporary Status and Regularisation) Scheme of Government of India, 1993\'.','The rules apply only if the individual received regular appointment in Government service regardless of continuity in service','The rules apply only if the individual was granted temporary status under the "Casual Labourers (Grant of Temporary Status and Regularisation) Scheme of Government of India, 1993\'.','Rule 2(4): CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, shall apply to persons who were regularly appointed in Government service after 31st December, 2003 but were conferred temporary status on or before 31st December, 2003 in accordance with the "Casual Labourers (Grant of Temporary Status and Regularisation) Scheme of Government of India, 1993" notified by Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions (Department of Personnel and Training) and such temporary status is followed without interruption by regular appointment in Government service.'],
['Which of the following cases will the benefits of Invalid Pension under rule 39 and Family Pension under rule 50 be payable to the Government servant or his family?','For a government servant who retired before December 31, 2003, and is not covered by any pension rules.','For a government servant who was appointed after December 31, 2003, and has exercised the option to this effect under rule 10 of the Central Civil Services (Implementation of National Pension System) Rules, 2021.','For a government servant who was appointed after December 31, 2003 and not covered by the Central Civil Services (Implementation of National Pension System) Rules, 2021.','For a government servant who was appointed before December 31, 2003, and is covered by the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972.','For a government servant who was appointed after December 31, 2003, and has exercised the option to this effect under rule 10 of the Central Civil Services (Implementation of National Pension System) Rules, 2021.','Rule 2(5): The CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, shall apply to the cases where in the event of death or discharge from service on the ground of invalidation in the case of a Government servant who, having been appointed to civil services and posts in connection with the affairs of the Union after 31st day of December, 2003, is covered by the Central Civil Services (Implementation of National Pension System) Rules, 2021, the benefits of Invalid Pension under rule 39 and Family Pension under rule 50 shall be payable to the Government servant or his family, as the case may be, if the Government servant had exercised an option to this effect under rule 10 of the Central Civil Services (Implementation of National Pension System) Rules, 2021 or in whose case the default option is for availing benefits under these rules or the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972'],
['What is true when a Government servant is transferred from a post or service where different pension rules apply to a post where CCS (Pension) Rules apply?',' The Government servant becomes subject to the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer.','The Government servant has the option to elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer within six months of the date of issue of the order of his permanent transfer.','The Government servant cannot elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer.','None of the above','The Government servant has the option to elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer within six months of the date of issue of the order of his permanent transfer.',' Rule 4. Government servants transferred from services and posts to which these rules do not apply.- \n(1) A Government servant who is transferred permanently to a service or post to which these rules apply from a service or post to which these rules do not apply shall become subject to these rules: Provided that it shall be open to him, within six months of the date of issue of the order of his permanent transfer or, if he is on leave on that day, then, within six months of his return from leave, whichever is later, to elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer. \n(2) The option under the proviso to sub-rule (1) shall be exercised in writing and communicated to the authority making such order of transfer. \n(3) The option, once exercised, shall be final.'],
['When a government servant (governed by different pension rules) is permanently transferred to a post or service that falls under the CCS Pension Rules, 2021, they become subject to these rules. In this context, which of the following is correct:','The Government servant has the option to elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer within six months of the date of issue of the order of his permanent transfer.','The option under the proviso to sub-rule shall be exercised in writing and communicated to the authority making such order of transfer.','The option, once exercised, shall be final.','All of the above','All of the above',' Rule 4. Government servants transferred from services and posts to which these rules do not apply.- \n(1) A Government servant who is transferred permanently to a service or post to which these rules apply from a service or post to which these rules do not apply shall become subject to these rules: Provided that it shall be open to him, within six months of the date of issue of the order of his permanent transfer or, if he is on leave on that day, then, within six months of his return from leave, whichever is later, to elect to be governed by the pension rules to which he was subject immediately before the date of his transfer. \n(2) The option under the proviso to sub-rule (1) shall be exercised in writing and communicated to the authority making such order of transfer. \n(3) The option, once exercised, shall be final.'],
['In the context of CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, which of the following is correct: \n1. Any claim to pension or family pension shall be regulated by the provisions of these rules in force at the time when a Government servant is appointed. \n2. Government servants\' date of retirement, discharge, resignation or death will be considered as their last working day (except when on leave or under suspension).','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','2 only',' Rule 5: Claims to pension or family pension- \n(1) Any claim to pension or family pension shall be regulated by the provisions of these rules in force at the time when a Government servant retires or is retired or is discharged or is allowed to resign from service or dies, as the case may be. \n(2) The day on which a Government servant retires or is retired or is discharged or is allowed to resign from service, as the case may be, shall be treated as his last completed working day and the date of death shall also be treated as a completed working day. \nProvided that in a case where the Government servant immediately before his retirement or death was absent from duty on leave or otherwise or was under suspension, the day of retirement or death shall be part of such leave or absence or suspension.'],
['Which of the following is correct? \n1. A Government servant shall not earn two pensions in the same service or post at the same time or by the same continuous service. \n2. Re-employed Government servants who have retired on a superannuation pension or retiring pension are not eligible for a separate pension or gratuity. \n3. Re-employed Government servants who are receiving a compassionate allowance after being dismissed or removed from service are eligible for a separate pension or gratuity.','1 and 2 only','3 only','2 only','All of the above','1 and 2 only','Rule 6: (1) A Government servant shall not earn two pensions in the same service or post at the same time or by the same continuous service. \n(2) Except as provided in rule 19 or rule 20, a Government servant who, having retired on a superannuation pension or retiring pension or compulsory retirement pension or who is in receipt of a compassionate allowance on having been dismissed or removed from service, is subsequently re-employed, shall not be entitled to a separate pension or gratuity for the period of his re-employment. \nA government servant who was previously appointed in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and later appointed in government service before December 31, 2003, is eligible for pension and gratuity for service rendered in the government in addition to the pension and gratuity received from the previous appointment. \nThe total amount of gratuity for both services shall not exceed what would have been admissible based on the entire service rendered and emoluments on retirement from government service.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. A Govt. servant previously appointed in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and subsequently in Govt. service (before Dec. 31, 2003) is eligible for pension and gratuity for both services. \n2. the total gratuity for both services cannot exceed what is admissible based on the entire service and emoluments on retirement.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 6: (1) A Government servant shall not earn two pensions in the same service or post at the same time or by the same continuous service. \n(2) Except as provided in rule 19 or rule 20, a Government servant who, having retired on a superannuation pension or retiring pension or compulsory retirement pension or who is in receipt of a compassionate allowance on having been dismissed or removed from service, is subsequently re-employed, shall not be entitled to a separate pension or gratuity for the period of his re-employment. \nA government servant who was previously appointed in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and later appointed in government service before December 31, 2003, is eligible for pension and gratuity for service rendered in the government in addition to the pension and gratuity received from the previous appointment. \nThe total amount of gratuity for both services shall not exceed what would have been admissible based on the entire service rendered and emoluments on retirement from government service.'],
['A government servant who previously worked in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and was subsequently appointed in the government service before 31st December 2003 is eligible for which of the following?','Pension and gratuity for their service rendered in the government only.','Pension and gratuity for their service rendered in the autonomous body or public sector undertaking only.','Pension and gratuity for their service rendered in both the government and autonomous body/public sector undertaking.','No pension or gratuity for their service rendered in either the government or autonomous body/public sector undertaking.','Pension and gratuity for their service rendered in both the government and autonomous body/public sector undertaking.','Rule 6: (1) A Government servant shall not earn two pensions in the same service or post at the same time or by the same continuous service. \n(2) Except as provided in rule 19 or rule 20, a Government servant who, having retired on a superannuation pension or retiring pension or compulsory retirement pension or who is in receipt of a compassionate allowance on having been dismissed or removed from service, is subsequently re-employed, shall not be entitled to a separate pension or gratuity for the period of his re-employment. \nA government servant who was previously appointed in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and later appointed in government service before December 31, 2003, is eligible for pension and gratuity for service rendered in the government in addition to the pension and gratuity received from the previous appointment. \nThe total amount of gratuity for both services shall not exceed what would have been admissible based on the entire service rendered and emoluments on retirement from government service.'],
['A Government employee who worked in an autonomous body or PSU and was appointed to the government service before December 31, 2003 is eligible for pension and gratuity from both the government and their previous employer. In this case who is responsible for paying the pension of a government employee for their service rendered in an autonomous body or PSU?','The Government','The autonomous body or public sector undertaking itself','Both the Government and the autonomous body or public sector undertaking','None of the above','The autonomous body or public sector undertaking itself','Rule 6: (1) A Government servant shall not earn two pensions in the same service or post at the same time or by the same continuous service. \n(2) Except as provided in rule 19 or rule 20, a Government servant who, having retired on a superannuation pension or retiring pension or compulsory retirement pension or who is in receipt of a compassionate allowance on having been dismissed or removed from service, is subsequently re-employed, shall not be entitled to a separate pension or gratuity for the period of his re-employment. \nA government servant who was previously appointed in an autonomous body or public sector undertaking and later appointed in government service before December 31, 2003, is eligible for pension and gratuity for service rendered in the government in addition to the pension and gratuity received from the previous appointment. \nThe total amount of gratuity for both services shall not exceed what would have been admissible based on the entire service rendered and emoluments on retirement from government service. \nPension, if any, on account of service rendered in an autonomous body or a public sector undertaking shall be paid by the concerned autonomous body or the public sector undertaking itself and there shall be no liability on the part of the Government towards pension for the service rendered by the Government servant in the said autonomous body or the public sector undertaking before joining service under the Government'],
[' The _________________ can withhold or withdraw a pension, either permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct. ','President','Appointing Authority','Secretary, D/o P&PW','Secretary of the concerned Ministry/ Department','Appointing Authority','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. \n(b) the Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct: Provided that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn, the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['Under what circumstances can the Appointing Authority withhold or withdraw a pension under these rules?','If any dependent family member of pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct','if there is any court case filed against the pensioner','If the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct','None of the above','If the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. \n(b) the Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct: Provided that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn, the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['Which of the following is/are true: \n1. The Appointing Authority can withhold or withdraw a pension, either permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct. \n2. The amount of such withheld or withdrawn pension shall not be less than the minimum pension under rule 44.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. \n(b) the Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct: Provided that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn, the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['Which of the following is/are true: \n1. The Appointing Authority can withhold or withdraw pension, permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct. \n2. If the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime, this action shall be taken in light of the judgment of the court relating to such conviction. \n3. If the pensioner is prima facie guilty of grave misconduct, the appointing authority must serve a notice to the pensioner specifying the proposed action and the ground.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','None of the above','1, 2 and 3','1, 2 and 3','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. \n(b) The Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct: Provided that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn, the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44. \n(2) Where a pensioner is convicted of a serious crime by a Court of Law, action under sub-rule (1) shall be taken in the light of the judgment of the court relating to such conviction. \n(3) In a case not falling under sub-rule (2), if the authority referred to in sub-rule (1) considers that the pensioner is prima facie guilty of grave misconduct, he shall before passing an order under sub-rule (1),- (a) serve upon the pensioner a notice specifying the action proposed to be taken against him and the ground on which it is proposed to be taken and calling upon him to submit, within fifteen days of the receipt of the notice or such further time not exceeding fifteen days, as may be allowed by the said authority, such representation, as he may wish to make against the proposal; and (b) take into consideration the representation, if any, submitted by the pensioner under Clause (a).'],
['If the pensioner is prima facie guilty of grave misconduct, the appointing authority must serve a notice to the pensioner specifying the proposed action and the ground, allowing the pensioner to submit a representation within ____________ . ','10 days','15 days','3 weeks','30 days','15 days','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. \n(b) The Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct: Provided that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn, the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44. \n(2) Where a pensioner is convicted of a serious crime by a Court of Law, action under sub-rule (1) shall be taken in the light of the judgment of the court relating to such conviction. \n(3) In a case not falling under sub-rule (2), if the authority referred to in sub-rule (1) considers that the pensioner is prima facie guilty of grave misconduct, he shall before passing an order under sub-rule (1),- (a) serve upon the pensioner a notice specifying the action proposed to be taken against him and the ground on which it is proposed to be taken and calling upon him to submit, within fifteen days of the receipt of the notice or such further time not exceeding fifteen days, as may be allowed by the said authority, such representation, as he may wish to make against the proposal; and (b) take into consideration the representation, if any, submitted by the pensioner under Clause (a).'],
['Which of the following is required for a government servant who has worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005, to make a publication after retirement?','Prior clearance from the Head of the Organization','Approval from the Ministry of Defense','Approval from the Prime Minister\'s Office','No clearance is required','Prior clearance from the Head of the Organization',''],
['Which of the following types of information is included in the publication restrictions for a retired government servant who has worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the 2nd Schedule to the RTI Act, 2005?','Any material relating to domain of the organization','Sensitive information which would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India.','Information, the disclosure of which would harm the security, strategic, scientific or economic interests of the State or relation with a foreign State.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 7(4)(a) Without prejudice to the provisions of sub-rule (3), no Government servant who having worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organisation included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005 (22 of 2005), shall, without prior clearance from the Head of the Organisation, make any publication after retirement of any material relating to and including,- \n(i) domain of the organisation, including any reference or information about any personnel and his designation, and expertise or knowledge gained by virtue of working in that organisation; and \n(ii) sensitive information, the disclosure of which would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security, strategic, scientific or economic interests of the State or relation with a foreign State, or which would lead to incitement of an offense.'],
['No government servant who has worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the ______________ to the Right to Information Act, 2005 shall make any publication after retirement without prior clearance from the Head of the Organization.','1st Schedule','2nd Schedule','3rd Schedule','4th Schedule','2nd Schedule','Rule 7(4)(a) Without prejudice to the provisions of sub-rule (3), no Government servant who having worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organisation included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005 (22 of 2005), shall, without prior clearance from the Head of the Organisation, make any publication after retirement of any material relating to and including,- \n(i) domain of the organisation, including any reference or information about any personnel and his designation, and expertise or knowledge gained by virtue of working in that organisation; and \n(ii) sensitive information, the disclosure of which would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security, strategic, scientific or economic interests of the State or relation with a foreign State, or which would lead to incitement of an offense.'],
['No government servant who has worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the Second Schedule to the __________________ shall make any publication after retirement without prior clearance from the Head of the Organization.','Official Secrets Act, 1923','National Security Act, 1980','Right to Information Act, 2005','Atomic Energy Act, 1962','Right to Information Act, 2005','Rule 7(4)(a) Without prejudice to the provisions of sub-rule (3), no Government servant who having worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organisation included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005 (22 of 2005), shall, without prior clearance from the Head of the Organisation, make any publication after retirement of any material relating to and including,- \n(i) domain of the organisation, including any reference or information about any personnel and his designation, and expertise or knowledge gained by virtue of working in that organisation; and \n(ii) sensitive information, the disclosure of which would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security, strategic, scientific or economic interests of the State or relation with a foreign State, or which would lead to incitement of an offense.'],
['Which of the following statements are true regarding the publication restrictions for retired government servants who have worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the 2nd Schedule to the RTI Act, 2005? \n1. Such government servants must give an undertaking in regard to the publication restrictions in a specific Format1. \n2. Any violation of the publication restrictions by a retired government servant would be considered a minor misconduct. \n3. The Head of the Organization has the authority to decide whether the proposed material for publication is sensitive or non-sensitive. \n4. The undertaking obtained from the Government servant must be kept in the service book ','1 and 3 only','2 and 4 only','1, 3 and 4','1, 2 and 4','1, 3 and 4','Rule 7(4): a) No government servant who has worked in an Intelligence or Security-related organization included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005 shall make any publication after retirement without prior clearance from the Head of the Organization. The publication includes any material relating to the domain of the organization, any reference or information about any personnel and his designation, and expertise or knowledge gained by working in that organization. The publication also includes sensitive information, the disclosure of which would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security, strategic, scientific, or economic interests of the State, or relation with a foreign State or which would lead to incitement of an offense. \nb) The Government servants who have worked in Intelligence or Security-related organizations included in the Second Schedule to the Right to Information Act, 2005. They are required to give an undertaking in Format1 agreeing to the restriction on publication of certain information after retirement without prior clearance. Any failure to observe this undertaking will be considered as grave misconduct. In case of transfer, the undertaking should be obtained in duplicate and kept in the service book of the government servant and the organization for record. \nRule 7(5)- The Head of the Organization has the authority to decide whether the proposed material for publication is sensitive or non-sensitive and falls in the organization\'s domain.'],
['Which of the following is correct? \n1. 1. The Appointing Authority can withhold or withdraw a pension, either permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or found guilty of grave misconduct. \n2. Where the authority competent to pass an order is the President, the UPSC need not be consulted before any order is passed. \n3. An appeal against such order passed by any authority other than President shall lie with the President who will consult with the UPSC before deciding on the appeal.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','None of the above','1 and 3 only','Rule 7- Pension and family pension subject to future good conduct.- \n(1)(a) Future good conduct shall be an implied condition of every grant of pension and its continuance under these rules. (b) the Appointing Authority may, by order in writing, withhold or withdraw a pension or a part thereof, whether permanently or for a specified period, if the pensioner is convicted of a serious crime or is found guilty of grave misconduct. \n7(6) Where the authority competent to pass an order under sub-rule (1) is the President, the Union Public Service Commission shall be consulted before any order is passed. \n7(7) An appeal against an order under sub-rule (1), passed by any authority other than President, shall lie to the President and the President shall, in consultation with the Union Public Service Commission, pass such orders on the appeal as he deems fit.'],
['What is the role of the Union Public Service Commission in the process of withholding or withdrawing a pension or gratuity?','They have the power to withhold or withdraw the pension themselves','They must be consulted before any final orders are passed by the President','They are responsible for determining the amount of the pension or gratuity','They are responsible for investigating the alleged misconduct or negligence of the retired employee','They must be consulted before any final orders are passed by the President','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension - \n(1) The President reserves to himself the right of withholding a pension or gratuity, or both, either in full or in part, or withdrawing a pension in full or in part, whether permanently or for a specified period, and of ordering recovery from a pension or gratuity of the whole or part of any pecuniary loss caused to the Government, if, in any departmental or judicial proceedings, the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the period of service, including service rendered upon re-employment after retirement : Provided that the Union Public Service Commission shall be consulted before any final orders are passed: Provided further that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['In the context of the Power to withhold or withdraw pension, which of the following is correct: \n1. President can withhold/withdraw pension or gratuity, in full or in part, if the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the service period, including re-employment after retirement. \n2. Such order can be for a specified period or permanent in nature, and recovery of any pecuniary loss caused to the government can also be ordered. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension - \n(1) The President reserves to himself the right of withholding a pension or gratuity, or both, either in full or in part, or withdrawing a pension in full or in part, whether permanently or for a specified period, and of ordering recovery from a pension or gratuity of the whole or part of any pecuniary loss caused to the Government, if, in any departmental or judicial proceedings, the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the period of service, including service rendered upon re-employment after retirement : Provided that the Union Public Service Commission shall be consulted before any final orders are passed: Provided further that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['When the President decides to withhold or withdraw a pension or gratuity, either in full or in part then in such cases: \n1. The Union Public Service Commission must be consulted before any final orders are passed. \n2. If a part of the pension is withheld or withdrawn, it cannot be reduced below the minimum pension amount under Rule 44.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension - \n(1) The President reserves to himself the right of withholding a pension or gratuity, or both, either in full or in part, or withdrawing a pension in full or in part, whether permanently or for a specified period, and of ordering recovery from a pension or gratuity of the whole or part of any pecuniary loss caused to the Government, if, in any departmental or judicial proceedings, the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the period of service, including service rendered upon re-employment after retirement : Provided that the Union Public Service Commission shall be consulted before any final orders are passed: Provided further that where a part of pension is withheld or withdrawn the amount of such pension shall not be reduced below the amount of minimum pension under rule 44.'],
['Which of the following conditions are correct for instituting departmental proceedings after retirement? \n1. It shall not be instituted without the sanction of the President. \n2. It shall not relate to an event that took place more than five years before the institution of the proceedings. \n3. The pensioner concerned shall receive a memorandum of charges in Format 3 for the purpose of instituting the departmental proceedings.','1 only','1 and 3 only','2 and 3 only','All of the above','1 and 3 only','Rule 8- \n2(c): The departmental proceedings, if not instituted while the Government servant was in service, whether before his retirement, or during his re-employment, - \n(i) shall not be instituted save with the sanction of the President in Format 2; \n(ii) shall not be in respect of any event which took place more than four years before such institution; and \n(iii) shall be conducted by such authority and in such place as the President may direct and in accordance with the procedure applicable to departmental proceedings in which an order of dismissal from service could be made in relation to the Government servant during his service: Provided that for the purpose of instituting departmental proceedings under this sub-rule, a memorandum of charges shall be communicated to the pensioner concerned in Format 3.'],
['Select the correct statement(s): \n1. Departmental proceedings initiated while the government servant was in service shall continue after retirement as if the employee was still in service. \n2. If the departmental proceedings were initiated by an authority subordinate to the President, the findings shall be submitted to the President for a final decision. \n3. Departmental proceedings initiated under Rule 16 of the CCS (CCA) Rules, 1965, while the government servant was in service would automatically freeze the pension and gratuity.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','None of the above','1 and 2 only','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension. \n(2)(a) The departmental proceedings referred to in sub-rule (1), if instituted while the Government servant was in service whether before his retirement or during his re-employment, shall, after the final retirement of the Government servant, be deemed to be proceedings under this rule and shall be continued and concluded by the authority by which they were commenced in the same manner as if the Government servant had continued in service: Provided that in all cases where the departmental proceedings are instituted by an authority subordinate to the President, that authority shall submit a report recording its findings to the President and the President shall take the final decision in the matter in accordance with sub-rule (1). \n(b) Notwithstanding anything mentioned in sub-rule (1) and clause (a), departmental proceedings instituted under rule 16 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965, while the Government servant was in service and continued after retirement, shall have no effect on the pension and gratuity of the pensioner.'],
['The Departmental proceedings not initiated during a government servant\'s service shall follow the same procedures as _________________ and be conducted as directed by the President.','Minor Penalty Proceedings','Appeal Proceedings','Dismissal Proceedings','None of the above','Dismissal Proceedings','Rule 8- \n2(c): The departmental proceedings, if not instituted while the Government servant was in service, whether before his retirement, or during his re-employment, - \n(i) shall not be instituted save with the sanction of the President in Format 2; \n(ii) shall not be in respect of any event which took place more than four years before such institution; and \n(iii) shall be conducted by such authority and in such place as the President may direct and in accordance with the procedure applicable to departmental proceedings in which an order of dismissal from service could be made in relation to the Government servant during his service: Provided that for the purpose of instituting departmental proceedings under this sub-rule, a memorandum of charges shall be communicated to the pensioner concerned in Format 3.'],
['What is the situation in which the CCS (Pension) Rules 1972 provide for the sanctioning of provisional pension?','When a retired government servant against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued. ','When departmental proceedings instituted under rule 16 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965, while the Government servant was in service and continued after retirement.','Provisional Pension is sanctioned only with the approval of the President','None of the above','When a retired government servant against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued. ','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension. \nRule 8(3): In the case of Government servant who has retired on attaining the age of superannuation or otherwise and against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued under sub- rule (2), a provisional pension as provided in sub-rule (4) shall be sanctioned.'],
['Which of the following statement(s) is/are correct? \n1. The provisional pension is equal to the maximum pension that would have been admissible on the basis of qualifying service up to the date of retirement. \n2. The provisional pension is equal to the maximum pension that would have been admissible on the basis of qualifying service up to the date immediately preceding the suspension if the servant was under suspension on the date of retirement. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 8(3) and 8(4a): \n The Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972 provides for the sanctioning of provisional pension to a retired government servant against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued. The Accounts Officer shall authorize the provisional pension for a government servant which will be equal to the maximum pension that would have been granted based on qualifying service up to the date of retirement or the date immediately preceding the suspension if the servant was under suspension on the date of retirement.'],
['Which of the following is correct in the context of Provisional Pension: \n1. The Accounts Officer will authorize the provisional pension starting from the day after retirement until the date of final orders passed by the competent authority after departmental or judicial proceedings. \n2. Gratuity will be paid in full immediately after retirement. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 8(3): \n The Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972 provides for the sanctioning of provisional pension to a retired government servant against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued. \nRule 8(4b): The provisional pension shall be authorised by the Accounts Officer during the period commencing from the date following the date of retirement up to and including the date on which, after the conclusion of departmental or judicial proceedings, final orders are passed by the competent authority. \nRule 8(4c) No gratuity shall be paid to the Government servant until the conclusion of the departmental or judicial proceedings and issue of final orders thereon.'],
['Which of the following situations would not qualify for provisional pension under the CCS (Pension) Rules 1972?','A retired government servant against whom departmental proceedings were instituted during service and are ongoing.','A retired government servant against whom allegations of misconduct are under investigation.','A retired government servant against whom departmental or judicial proceedings are contemplated but have not been instituted or deemed to have been instituted till the date of retirement of the Government servant.','When a Govt. Servant is served with a charge sheet on the day of his retirement.','A retired government servant against whom departmental or judicial proceedings are contemplated but have not been instituted or deemed to have been instituted till the date of retirement of the Government servant.','Rule 8(3): In the case of Government servant who has retired on attaining the age of superannuation or otherwise and against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued, a provisional pension as provided in sub-rule (4) shall be sanctioned. \nRule 8(4d): The provisions of this sub-rule shall not be applicable where allegations of misconduct are under investigation against a Government servant or where departmental or judicial proceedings are contemplated against a Government servant but have not actually been instituted or deemed to have been instituted till the date of retirement of the Government servant. The pension and gratuity in such cases shall be authorised to be paid to the Government servant on his retirement in accordance with rule 63.'],
['The pension and gratuity in cases where departmental or judicial proceedings are contemplated against a Government servant but have not actually been instituted shall be authorised to be paid to the Government servant on his retirement in accordance with _________.','Rule 61','Rule 62','Rule 63','Rule 64','Rule 63','Rule 8(3): In the case of Government servant who has retired on attaining the age of superannuation or otherwise and against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the Central Civil Services (Classification, Control and Appeal) Rules, 1965 are continued, a provisional pension as provided in sub-rule (4) shall be sanctioned. \nRule 8(4d): The provisions of this sub-rule shall not be applicable where allegations of misconduct are under investigation against a Government servant or where departmental or judicial proceedings are contemplated against a Government servant but have not actually been instituted or deemed to have been instituted till the date of retirement of the Government servant. The pension and gratuity in such cases shall be authorised to be paid to the Government servant on his retirement in accordance with rule 63.'],
['Which of the following is correct with regard to Provisional Pension? \n1. Payment of provisional pension made to the retired Govt. Servant shall be adjusted against final retirement benefits sanctioned to such Government servant upon conclusion of such proceedings. \n2. Recovery shall be made where the pension finally sanctioned is less than the provisional pension or the pension is reduced or withheld either permanently or for a specified period. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 8(3): In the case of Government servant who has retired on attaining the age of superannuation or otherwise and against whom any departmental or judicial proceedings are instituted or where departmental proceedings instituted under rule 14 of the CCS (CCA) Rules, 1965 are continued, a provisional pension as provided in sub-rule (4) shall be sanctioned. \nRule 8(5) Payment of provisional pension made under sub-rule (4) shall be adjusted against final retirement benefits sanctioned to such Government servant upon conclusion of such proceedings but no recovery shall be made where the pension finally sanctioned is less than the provisional pension or the pension is reduced or withheld either permanently or for a specified period.'],
['The recovery of pecuniary loss from a retired government servant\'s pension, as per the President\'s order, should not exceed __________ of the pension admissible on the date of retirement.','one-fourth','one-third','one-fifth','one-half','one-third','Rule 8(6): Where the President decides not to withhold or withdraw pension but orders recovery of pecuniary loss from pension, the recovery shall not ordinarily be made at a rate exceeding one-third of the pension admissible on the date of retirement of a Government servant.'],
['According to the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 2021, the President may revise any order made under these rules after consultation with the Union Public Service Commission. Which of the following statements is NOT true regarding this provision?','The President has the authority to withhold or withdraw a pension or gratuity, in whole or in part, for a specified period or permanently.','The President may enhance the amount of pension or gratuity to be withheld or withdrawn without giving the concerned government servant a reasonable opportunity to make a representation.','The President can review any order made under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules and modify or set it aside, after consulting with the Union Public Service Commission.','The President may remit the case to any authority directing them to make further inquiry. ','The President may enhance the amount of pension or gratuity to be withheld or withdrawn without giving the concerned government servant a reasonable opportunity to make a representation.','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension .- (1) The President reserves to himself the right of withholding a pension or gratuity, or both, either in full or in part, or withdrawing a pension in full or in part, whether permanently or for a specified period, and of ordering recovery from a pension or gratuity of the whole or part of any pecuniary loss caused to the Government, if, in any departmental or judicial proceedings, the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the period of service, including service rendered upon re-employment after retirement. \nRule 8(7): The President may at any time, either on his own motion or otherwise call for the records of any inquiry and revise any order made under these rules, after consultation with the Union Public Service Commission, and may confirm, modify or set aside the order; or remit the case to any authority directing such authority to make such further enquiry as it may consider proper in the circumstances of the case or pass such other order as he may deem fit: Provided that no order enhancing the amount of pension or gratuity to be withheld or withdrawn, shall be made by the President unless the Government servant concerned has been given a reasonable opportunity of making a representation against the order proposed and except after consultation with the Union Public Service Commission. '],
['As per CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, the judicial proceedings shall be deemed to be instituted when: \n1. The complaint or report of a police officer is made in the case of criminal proceedings. \n2. The date of first hearing in court in case of civil proceedings.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','For the purpose of CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021- (1)(a) Departmental proceedings shall be deemed to be instituted on the date on which the statement of charges is issued to the Government servant or pensioner, or if the Government servant has been placed under suspension from an earlier date, on such date; and \n(b) Judicial proceedings shall be deemed to be instituted (i) in the case of criminal proceedings, on the date on which the complaint or report of a police officer, of which the Magistrate takes cognizance, is made; and (ii) in the case of civil proceedings, on the date the suit is filed in the court.'],
['The President has the right to withhold or withdraw a pension or gratuity, and order recovery of any pecuniary loss caused to the government. This action may be taken if the pensioner is found guilty of: \n1. Any corrupt practices during service. \n2. Any misconduct whether in relation to the performance of official duty or otherwise. \n3. Any misconduct whether resulting in pecuniary loss to the Government or otherwise.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','None of the above','1, 2 and 3','Rule 8- Power to withhold or withdraw pension .- (1) The President reserves to himself the right of withholding a pension or gratuity, or both, either in full or in part, or withdrawing a pension in full or in part, whether permanently or for a specified period, and of ordering recovery from a pension or gratuity of the whole or part of any pecuniary loss caused to the Government, if, in any departmental or judicial proceedings, the pensioner is found guilty of grave misconduct or negligence during the period of service, including service rendered upon re-employment after retirement. \nExplanation 3: (3) action under sub-rule (1) may be taken, if the pensioner is found guilty of,- \n(i) any corrupt practices during service; \n(ii) any misconduct whether in relation to the performance of official duty or otherwise; and \n(iii) any misconduct whether resulting in pecuniary loss to the Government or otherwise. '],
['A pensioner who was a member of Central Service __________ before retirement must obtain prior sanction from the Government to accept any commercial employment within one year of retirement.','Group A','Group A or B','Group C','Group A, B or C','Group A','Rule 9: Commercial employment after retirement.\n If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance by submitting an application in Form 1: Provided that a Government servant who was permitted by the Government to take up a particular form of commercial employment during his leave preparatory to retirement or during refused leave shall not be required to obtain subsequent permission for his continuance in such employment after retirement. \nProvided further that a Government servant shall not negotiate for commercial employment during service without prior permission of the administrative Ministry or Department and such permission shall not be given unless there are special reasons for doing so.'],
['A pensioner who retired as Group A and desirous of accepting any commercial employment within one year of his retirement shall obtain the sanction of the Government by submitting an application in ___________. ','Form 1','Form 2','Form 3','Form 4','Form 1','Rule 9: Commercial employment after retirement.\n If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance by submitting an application in Form 1: Provided that a Government servant who was permitted by the Government to take up a particular form of commercial employment during his leave preparatory to retirement or during refused leave shall not be required to obtain subsequent permission for his continuance in such employment after retirement. \nProvided further that a Government servant shall not negotiate for commercial employment during service without prior permission of the administrative Ministry or Department and such permission shall not be given unless there are special reasons for doing so.'],
['With regard to commercial employment after retirement, which of the following is/are correct? ','The Government may, by order in writing, on an application made by a pensioner, grant necessary permission subject to subject to such conditions, if any, as it may deem necessary.','While refusing the permission to take up the commercial employment specified in the application, the reasons need not be recorded in writing. ','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','The Government may, by order in writing, on an application made by a pensioner, grant necessary permission subject to subject to such conditions, if any, as it may deem necessary.',''],
['What factors are to be kept in perspective while granting or refusing permission to a pensioner for taking up any commercial employment? \n1. Whether NOC has been obtained from Cadre Controlling Authority and and from the office where the officer retired. \n2. Whether officer has been privy to sensitive or strategic information in the last three years related to the organisation or areas of interest or work they propose to join or consult. \n3. Whether there exist a conflict of interest between the policies of the office he has held and the organisation he proposes to join.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','2 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','Rule 9: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance \n(3) In granting or refusing permission under sub-rule (2) to a pensioner for taking up any commercial employment, the Government shall have regard to the following factors, namely:- \na) Whether \'No Object\' for the proposed post retirement commercial employment has been obtained from the cadre controlling authority and from the office where the officer retired; \n(b) whether the officer has been privy to sensitive or strategic information in the last three years of his service which is directly related to the areas of interest or work of the organisation which he proposes to join or the areas in which he proposes to practise or consult; \n(c) whether there is conflict of interest between the policies of the office he has held in the last three years and the interest represented or work undertaken by the organisation he proposes to join; Explanation.- For the purpose of this clause, "Conflict of Interest" shall not include normal economic competition with the Government or its undertakings. \n(d) whether the organisation he proposes to join has been known to be in any way in conflict with or prejudicial to India\'s foreign relations and national security and domestic harmony, and whether the organisation is undertaking any activity for intelligence gathering; \n(e) whether service record of the officer is clear, particularly with respect to integrity and dealings with nonGovernment organisations; \n(f) whether the proposed emoluments and pecuniary benefits are far in excess of those currently prevailing in the industry; \n(g) any other relevant factor which may be in the knowledge of the administrative Ministry but are not included in the criteria in this rule or the matters on which specific instructions may be issued by Department of Personnel and Training from time to time.'],
['What considerations should be taken into account while granting or refusing permission to a pensioner for taking up any commercial employment? \n1. whether the organisation he proposes to join has been known to be in any way in conflict with or prejudicial to India\'s national security and domestic harmony, and whether the organisation is undertaking any activity for intelligence gathering;. \n2. whether service record of the officer is clear, particularly with respect to integrity and dealings with nonGovernment organisations. \n3. whether the duties of the commercial employment proposed involve liaison or contact work with Government departments.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','2 and 3 only','1 and 2 only','Rule 9: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance \n(3) In granting or refusing permission under sub-rule (2) to a pensioner for taking up any commercial employment, the Government shall have regard to the following factors, namely:- \na) Whether \'No Object\' for the proposed post retirement commercial employment has been obtained from the cadre controlling authority and from the office where the officer retired; \n(b) whether the officer has been privy to sensitive or strategic information in the last three years of his service which is directly related to the areas of interest or work of the organisation which he proposes to join or the areas in which he proposes to practise or consult; \n(c) whether there is conflict of interest between the policies of the office he has held in the last three years and the interest represented or work undertaken by the organisation he proposes to join; Explanation.- For the purpose of this clause, "Conflict of Interest" shall not include normal economic competition with the Government or its undertakings. \n(d) whether the organisation he proposes to join has been known to be in any way in conflict with or prejudicial to India\'s foreign relations and national security and domestic harmony, and whether the organisation is undertaking any activity for intelligence gathering; \n(e) whether service record of the officer is clear, particularly with respect to integrity and dealings with nonGovernment organisations; \n(f) whether the proposed emoluments and pecuniary benefits are far in excess of those currently prevailing in the industry; \n(g) any other relevant factor which may be in the knowledge of the administrative Ministry but are not included in the criteria in this rule or the matters on which specific instructions may be issued by Department of Personnel and Training from time to time.'],
['While granting or refusing permission to pensioner for taking up commercial employement, which of the following aspect is NOT to be considered? ','whether the proposed emoluments and pecuniary benefits are far in excess of those currently prevailing in the industry','whether the organisation he proposes to join is in normal economic competition with Govt. or its undertakings','whether the organisation he proposes to join has been known to be in any way in conflict with or prejudicial to India\'s foreign relations','whether service record of the officer is clear, particularly with respect to integrity and dealings with non Government organisations','whether the organisation he proposes to join is in normal economic competition with Govt. or its undertakings','Rule 9: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance \n(3) In granting or refusing permission under sub-rule (2) to a pensioner for taking up any commercial employment, the Government shall have regard to the following factors, namely:- \na) Whether \'No Object\' for the proposed post retirement commercial employment has been obtained from the cadre controlling authority and from the office where the officer retired; \n(b) whether the officer has been privy to sensitive or strategic information in the last three years of his service which is directly related to the areas of interest or work of the organisation which he proposes to join or the areas in which he proposes to practise or consult; \n(c) whether there is conflict of interest between the policies of the office he has held in the last three years and the interest represented or work undertaken by the organisation he proposes to join; Explanation.- For the purpose of this clause, "Conflict of Interest" shall not include normal economic competition with the Government or its undertakings. \n(d) whether the organisation he proposes to join has been known to be in any way in conflict with or prejudicial to India\'s foreign relations and national security and domestic harmony, and whether the organisation is undertaking any activity for intelligence gathering; \n(e) whether service record of the officer is clear, particularly with respect to integrity and dealings with nonGovernment organisations; \n(f) whether the proposed emoluments and pecuniary benefits are far in excess of those currently prevailing in the industry; \n(g) any other relevant factor which may be in the knowledge of the administrative Ministry but are not included in the criteria in this rule or the matters on which specific instructions may be issued by Department of Personnel and Training from time to time.'],
['The applications of pensioners for permission to accept commercial employment shall be considered in accordance with the ______________ and the instructions issued by the Government from time to time.','Government of India (Allocation of Business) Rules, 1961','Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961','Rule 9: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance. \n9(4): The applications of pensioners for permission to accept commercial employment shall be considered in accordance with the Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961 and the instructions issued by the Government from time to time.'],
['When considering granting or denying permission for a pensioner to engage in commercial employment, the government will consider various factors. To ensure that all aspects of the case have been appropriately addressed, the administrative Ministry or Department must maintain a checklist in __________.','Form 1','Form 2','Form 3','Form 4','Form 2','Rule 9: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance. \n9(5): In order to ensure that all aspects relating to the case have received proper attention, the administrative Ministry or Department shall maintain a check list in Form 2.'],
['When considering granting or denying permission for a pensioner to engage in commercial employment, the government will consider various factors. If the pensioner is not disqualified on any grounds, the Government may:','grant permission for directorship of a company, consultancy work, or professional practice liberally','actively encourage post-service employment in fields such as science, literature, culture, social work, and the arts','The Government may be liberal in granting permission for positions of responsibility in the non-governmental sector.','All of the above','All of the above','If the pensioner is not disqualified on any grounds, the Government may: \n(i) Grant permission for directorship of a company, consultancy work, or professional practice liberally. \n(ii) Actively encourage post-service employment in fields such as science, literature, culture, social work, and the arts. \n(iii) Be liberal in granting permission for positions of responsibility in the non-governmental sector. (iv) Not differentiate between honorary, paid employment, and self-employment.'],
['If the government grants permission subject to any condition or denies permission for a pensioner to engage in commercial employment, the applicant may file a representation against any condition or refusal within ______________ of receiving the order.','15 days','30 days','45 days','60 days','30 days','Rule 9(1): Commercial Employment after retirement: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance by submitting an application in Form 1. \nRule 9(7): Where the Government grants the permission applied for subject to any conditions or refuses such permission, the applicant may, within thirty days of the receipt of the order of the Government to that effect, make a representation against any such condition or refusal and the Government may make such orders thereon as it deems fit.'],
['What factors must the government consider when making an order to declare that a pensioner is not entitled to their pension for engaging in commercial employment without prior permission?','The nature and emoluments of the commercial employment taken up','The financial circumstances of the pensioner','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 9(1): Commercial Employment after retirement: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance by submitting an application in Form 1. \nRule 9(8): If a pensioner engages in commercial employment within one year of their retirement without prior government permission or breaches any conditions attached to such permission, the government can issue a written order declaring that the pensioner is not entitled to all or part of their pension for a specified period. The pensioner must be given an opportunity to show cause against such a declaration. When making such an order, the government will consider the pensioner\'s financial situation, the nature and emoluments of the commercial employment, and any other relevant factors.'],
['What consequences can a pensioner face for engaging in commercial employment without prior permission or breaching any conditions, and what factors will be considered by the government when making such an order?','The government can issue a written order declaring that the pensioner is not entitled to all or part of their pension for a specified period. ','The factors considered by the government will include the nature of the commercial employment, the financial circumstances of the pensioner, and any other relevant factor.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 9(1): Commercial Employment after retirement: If a pensioner who, immediately before his retirement was a member of Central Service Group `A\' wishes to accept any commercial employment before the expiry of one year from the date of his retirement, he shall obtain the previous sanction of the Government to such acceptance by submitting an application in Form 1. \nRule 9(8): If a pensioner engages in commercial employment within one year of their retirement without prior government permission or breaches any conditions attached to such permission, the government can issue a written order declaring that the pensioner is not entitled to all or part of their pension for a specified period. The pensioner must be given an opportunity to show cause against such a declaration. When making such an order, the government will consider the pensioner\'s financial situation, the nature and emoluments of the commercial employment, and any other relevant factors.'],
['Select the correct statement regarding the definition of "Commercial Employment" under CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021: \n1. It includes employment in a company, co-operative society, firm, or individual engaged in trading, commercial, industrial, financial or professional business. \n2. It includes employment under a co-operative society as an office-bearer.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 9 (Commercial Employment after retirement) Explanation - For the purpose of this rule- (a) the expression "commercial employment" means :- \n(i) an employment in any capacity including that of an agent, under a company, co-operative society (which includes holding of any office, whether elective or otherwise, such as that of President, Chairman, Manager, Secretary, Treasurer and the like, by whatever name called in such society), firm or individual engaged in trading, commercial, industrial, financial or professional business and includes also a directorship of such company and partnership of such firm, but does not include employment under a body corporate, wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government; \n(ii) setting up practice, either independently or as a partner of a firm, as adviser or consultant in matters in respect of which the pensioner - \n(A) has no professional qualifications and the matters in respect of which the practice is to be set up or is carried on are relatable to his official knowledge or experience; or \b(B) has professional qualifications but the matters in respect of which such practice is to be set up are such as are likely to give his clients an unfair advantage by reason of his previous official position; or \n(C) has to undertake work involving liaison or contact with the offices or officers of the Government.'],
['Which of the following statements is/are included in the definition of "Commercial Employment" as per the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021? \n1. Employment in any capacity under a body corporate owned by the Central Government or a State Government. \n2. Employment in a company, co-operative society, firm, or individual engaged in trading, commercial, industrial, financial or professional business, including directorship or partnership. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','2 only','Rule 9 (Commercial Employment after retirement) Explanation - For the purpose of this rule- (a) the expression "commercial employment" means :- \n(i) an employment in any capacity including that of an agent, under a company, co-operative society (which includes holding of any office, whether elective or otherwise, such as that of President, Chairman, Manager, Secretary, Treasurer and the like, by whatever name called in such society), firm or individual engaged in trading, commercial, industrial, financial or professional business and includes also a directorship of such company and partnership of such firm, but does not include employment under a body corporate, wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government; \n(ii) setting up practice, either independently or as a partner of a firm, as adviser or consultant in matters in respect of which the pensioner - \n(A) has no professional qualifications and the matters in respect of which the practice is to be set up or is carried on are relatable to his official knowledge or experience; or \b(B) has professional qualifications but the matters in respect of which such practice is to be set up are such as are likely to give his clients an unfair advantage by reason of his previous official position; or \n(C) has to undertake work involving liaison or contact with the offices or officers of the Government.'],
['Which of the following is correct regarding the "Commercial Employment"?','It includes establishment of a practice as an adviser or consultant, either independently or as a partner of a firm in matters that are related to the pensioner\'s official knowledge or experience, even if the pensioner lacks professional qualifications in those matters.','It includes establishment of a practice as an adviser or consultant, either independently or as a partner of a firm in fields for which the pensioner has professional qualifications but are likely to give their clients an unfair advantage due to their previous official position.','In involves setting up practice, either independently or as a partner of a firm, as adviser or consultant in matters in respect of which the pensioner has to undertake work involving liaison or contact with the offices or officers of the Government.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 9 (Commercial Employment after retirement) Explanation - For the purpose of this rule- (a) the expression "commercial employment" means :- \n(i) an employment in any capacity including that of an agent, under a company, co-operative society (which includes holding of any office, whether elective or otherwise, such as that of President, Chairman, Manager, Secretary, Treasurer and the like, by whatever name called in such society), firm or individual engaged in trading, commercial, industrial, financial or professional business and includes also a directorship of such company and partnership of such firm, but does not include employment under a body corporate, wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government; \n(ii) setting up practice, either independently or as a partner of a firm, as adviser or consultant in matters in respect of which the pensioner - \n(A) has no professional qualifications and the matters in respect of which the practice is to be set up or is carried on are relatable to his official knowledge or experience; or \b(B) has professional qualifications but the matters in respect of which such practice is to be set up are such as are likely to give his clients an unfair advantage by reason of his previous official position; or \n(C) has to undertake work involving liaison or contact with the offices or officers of the Government.'],
['Under CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, what is the requirement for a pensioner who wishes to accept employment under any government outside India?','They must obtain prior permission from the Central Government if he was a member of Group \'A\' Central Service.','They must obtain prior permission from the Central Government along with Political Clearance from MEA.','They must obtain prior permission from the Central Government irrespective of his Group in Central Service.','They can accept employment under intimation to Central Govt.','They must obtain prior permission from the Central Government if he was a member of Group \'A\' Central Service.','Rule 10- Employment after retirement under a Government outside India. \nThis rule states that a Group `A\' pensioner of Central Service, who desires to accept employment under any government outside India after retirement, must seek prior permission from the Central Government. Failure to obtain permission could result in a loss of pension payments for the duration of the employment or a longer period as directed by the Government. However, if the Central Government had previously granted permission during the pensioner\'s leave preparatory to retirement, subsequent permission is not required. The request for permission will be evaluated according to the Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961 and other relevant instructions.'],
['If a pensioner accepts employment under a government outside India without proper permission, what may happen to their pension?','It will not be affected.','A part of the pension will be withheld.','No Pension shall be payablein respect of any period for which he is so employed or such longer period as the Government may direct.','The president may decide whether to withhold pension in part or in full.','No Pension shall be payablein respect of any period for which he is so employed or such longer period as the Government may direct.','Rule 10- Employment after retirement under a Government outside India. \nThis rule states that a Group `A\' pensioner of Central Service, who desires to accept employment under any government outside India after retirement, must seek prior permission from the Central Government. Failure to obtain permission could result in a loss of pension payments for the duration of the employment or a longer period as directed by the Government. However, if the Central Government had previously granted permission during the pensioner\'s leave preparatory to retirement, subsequent permission is not required. The request for permission will be evaluated according to the Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961 and other relevant instructions.'],
['In the context of securing employment after retirement under a Government outside India, which of the following option is correct? ','No pension shall be payable to a pensioner who accepts such an employment without proper permission in respect of any period for which he is so employed or such longer period as the Government may direct','Government servants who were allowed to work under any government outside India during their pre-retirement leave will not need further permission to continue such employment after retirement.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 10- Employment after retirement under a Government outside India. \nThis rule states that a Group `A\' pensioner of Central Service, who desires to accept employment under any government outside India after retirement, must seek prior permission from the Central Government. Failure to obtain permission could result in a loss of pension payments for the duration of the employment or a longer period as directed by the Government. However, if the Central Government had previously granted permission during the pensioner\'s leave preparatory to retirement, subsequent permission is not required. The request for permission will be evaluated according to the Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961 and other relevant instructions.'],
['A Group `A\' pensioner of Central Service, who desires to accept employment under any government outside India after retirement, must seek prior permission from the Central Government. Such requests for permission to work under a foreign government will be considered as per the _______________.','Government of India (Allocation of Business) Rules, 1961','Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961','Guidelines issued by the MEA','merits of each case','Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961','Rule 10- Employment after retirement under a Government outside India. \nThis rule states that a Group `A\' pensioner of Central Service, who desires to accept employment under any government outside India after retirement, must seek prior permission from the Central Government. Failure to obtain permission could result in a loss of pension payments for the duration of the employment or a longer period as directed by the Government. However, if the Central Government had previously granted permission during the pensioner\'s leave preparatory to retirement, subsequent permission is not required. The request for permission will be evaluated according to the Government of India (Transaction of Business) Rules, 1961 and other relevant instructions.'],
['Select the correct option regarding the Qualifying Service?','The qualifying service of a Government servant shall begin from the date he takes charge of the post to which he is first appointed either substantively or in an officiating or temporary capacity.','The officiating or temporary service will only count towards the qualifying service if it is followed without interruption by a substantive appointment in the same post only. ','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','The qualifying service of a Government servant shall begin from the date he takes charge of the post to which he is first appointed either substantively or in an officiating or temporary capacity.','Rule 11- Commencement of qualifying service- \nSubject to the provisions of these rules, qualifying service of a Government servant shall commence from the date he takes charge of the post to which he is first appointed either substantively or in an officiating or temporary capacity. \n Provided that officiating or temporary service is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the same or another service or post.\n Provided further that service rendered before attaining the age of eighteen years shall not count, except in the cases of counting of military service for civil pension under rule 20'],
['Which of the statement about Qualifying Service is accurate?','Service rendered before attaining the age of eighteen years shall not be counted, except in cases of counting military service for civil pension under rule 20.','The officiating or temporary service will only count towards the qualifying service if it is followed without interruption by a substantive appointment in the same or another service or post.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 11- Commencement of qualifying service- \nSubject to the provisions of these rules, qualifying service of a Government servant shall commence from the date he takes charge of the post to which he is first appointed either substantively or in an officiating or temporary capacity. \n Provided that officiating or temporary service is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the same or another service or post.\n Provided further that service rendered before attaining the age of eighteen years shall not count, except in the cases of counting of military service for civil pension under rule 20'],
['According to the CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021, what does the expression "Service" mean for the purpose of determining qualifying service?','Service under the Government and paid by that Government from any source.','Service under the Government and paid by that Government from the Consolidated Fund of India or a Local Fund administered by that Government.','Service under any organization paid by that organization from its own funds.','None of the above','Service under the Government and paid by that Government from the Consolidated Fund of India or a Local Fund administered by that Government.','Rule 12- Conditions subject to which service qualifies. \nThe service of a Government servant shall not qualify, unless his duties and pay are regulated by the Government, or under conditions determined by the Government. \nExplanation.- For the purposes of this rule, the expression "service" means service under the Government and paid by that Government from the Consolidated Fund of India or a Local Fund administered by that Government but does not include service in an establishment not having a non-contributory pension scheme, unless such service is treated as qualifying service by that Government.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct regarding the qualifying service? \n1. In order for a Government servant\'s service to qualify for their pension, their duties and pay must be regulated by the Government or under conditions set by the Government. \n2. Service in an establishment with a non-contributory pension scheme is also counted towards qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 12- Conditions subject to which service qualifies. \nThe service of a Government servant shall not qualify, unless his duties and pay are regulated by the Government, or under conditions determined by the Government. \nExplanation.- For the purposes of this rule, the expression "service" means service under the Government and paid by that Government from the Consolidated Fund of India or a Local Fund administered by that Government but does not include service in an establishment not having a non-contributory pension scheme, unless such service is treated as qualifying service by that Government.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct? \n1. Government servants of State Governments, appointed on or before 31st December, 2003 in a pensionable establishment, and permanently transferred to a service or post to which pension rules apply, shall have their continuous service under State counted as qualifying service. \n2. Service in temporary capacity in the State shall also be counted as qualifying service if followed by substantive appointment in State/Central Govt.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 13- Service in State Governments. \nA government servant belonging to a State Government who was initially appointed in a pensionable establishment of the State Government on or before December 31, 2003 and is permanently transferred to a service or post to which these rules apply, the continuous service rendered under the State Government in an officiating, temporary, or substantive capacity shall qualify. \nIf the continuous service rendered under that Government in an officiating or temporary capacity is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the State Government or the Central Government, it will qualify. In cases where a government servant belonging to a State Government is appointed with proper permission to a service or post to which these rules apply after accepting his resignation from the service of State Government, the continuous service rendered under the State Government in an officiating or temporary or substantive capacity shall qualify, subject to the condition that the service rendered under that Government in an officiating or temporary capacity is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the State Government or the Central Government. The liability for pension and gratuity in such cases shall be borne by the Central Government and no recovery of proportionate pension shall be made from the State Government.'],
['State Government servants appointed before 31 Dec 2003 in a pensionable establishment, when permanently transferred to a service or post where pension rules apply, their continuous service under State Government will qualify for pension. Who bears the liablity for Pension and Gratuity?','It shall be borne by the Central Government and no recovery of proportionate pension shall be made from the State Government. ','The Central Government will pay the full pension and the recovery of proportionate pension wiil be made from the State Government separtately. ','It will be borne by Central and State Govt. in proportion to the tenure under Central/ State Govt','None of the above','It shall be borne by the Central Government and no recovery of proportionate pension shall be made from the State Government. ','Rule 13- Service in State Governments. \nA government servant belonging to a State Government who was initially appointed in a pensionable establishment of the State Government on or before December 31, 2003 and is permanently transferred to a service or post to which these rules apply, the continuous service rendered under the State Government in an officiating, temporary, or substantive capacity shall qualify. \nIf the continuous service rendered under that Government in an officiating or temporary capacity is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the State Government or the Central Government, it will qualify. In cases where a government servant belonging to a State Government is appointed with proper permission to a service or post to which these rules apply after accepting his resignation from the service of State Government, the continuous service rendered under the State Government in an officiating or temporary or substantive capacity shall qualify, subject to the condition that the service rendered under that Government in an officiating or temporary capacity is followed without interruption by substantive appointment in the State Government or the Central Government. The liability for pension and gratuity in such cases shall be borne by the Central Government and no recovery of proportionate pension shall be made from the State Government.'],
['Under what circumstances will a Government servant be deemed to have been appointed in the Government with proper permission?','If the employee has applied for the service or post in the Government without previous permission of the State Govt.','The order of the State Govt. clearly indicates that the employee is resigning to join the post in the Government','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 13(2): A Government servant shall be deemed to have been appointed in the Government with proper per mission if he had applied for the service or post in the Government with previous permission of the State Government and the order of the State Government clearly indicates that the employee is resigning to join the post in the Government with proper permission of the State Government.'],
['Which of the following conditions must be met for a person appointed in an autonomous body under the Central Government or a State Government to qualify for pension under these rules after being appointed with proper permission to a service or post in the Central Government?','Continuous service under the autonomous body in a substantive capacity','Separate pension is not being drawn from the autonomous body','Pension liability is discharged by the autonomous body','All of the above','All of the above','The service rendered by a person in an autonomous body under the Central or State Government, having a non-contributory pension scheme, shall qualify for pension if: \n(a) the appointment of that Government servant in an officiating or temporary capacity in the Central Government is followed without interruption by substantive appointment; \n(b) the Government servant is not drawing a separate pension from the said autonomous body for the service rendered in that body before acceptance of resignation; and \n(c) the pension liability is discharged by the said Autonomous body by paying in lump sum the amount of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered in the autonomous body; and \n(d) the lump sum amount of pension shall be determined with reference to the commutation table laid down in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],
['The lump sum amount of pension for service rendered in an autonomous body under the Central/State Government before appointment to a service or post in the Central Government is determined with reference to?','The proportionate service rendered in the autonomous body','The commutation table laid down in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981','The prevalent non-contributory pension rules of the Autonomous Body','None of the above','The commutation table laid down in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981','The service rendered by a person in an autonomous body under the Central or State Government, having a non-contributory pension scheme, shall qualify for pension if: \n(a) the appointment of that Government servant in an officiating or temporary capacity in the Central Government is followed without interruption by substantive appointment; \n(b) the Government servant is not drawing a separate pension from the said autonomous body for the service rendered in that body before acceptance of resignation; and \n(c) the pension liability is discharged by the said Autonomous body by paying in lump sum the amount of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered in the autonomous body; and \n(d) the lump sum amount of pension shall be determined with reference to the commutation table laid down in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],
['Which of the following statement(s) is/are correct regarding the Service in Autonomous Bodies?','The service rendered by a person in an autonomous body under the Central or State Government, having a non-contributory pension scheme, shall qualify for pension if they are subsequently appointed to a service or post in the Central Government.','The service rendered in the autonomous body in an officiating or temporary capacity shall qualify if certain conditions are met, including that the person\'s appointment in the Central Government is uninterrupted and that the autonomous body discharges the pension liability.','Service rendered in a public sector undertaking, including nationalized bank and financial institution, before appointment in the Central Government shall not count as qualifying service.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 14: Service in Autonomous Bodies: \nThe service rendered by a person in an autonomous body under the Central or State Government, having a non-contributory pension scheme, shall qualify for pension if: \n(a) the appointment of that Government servant in an officiating or temporary capacity in the Central Government is followed without interruption by substantive appointment; \n(b) the Government servant is not drawing a separate pension from the said autonomous body for the service rendered in that body before acceptance of resignation; and \n(c) the pension liability is discharged by the said Autonomous body by paying in lump sum the amount of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered in the autonomous body; and \n(d) the lump sum amount of pension shall be determined with reference to the commutation table laid down in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. \n Service rendered in a public sector undertaking, including nationalized bank and financial institution, before appointment in the Central Government shall not count as qualifying service for the purpose of these rules.'],
['The service rendered in the autonomous body in an officiating, temporary, or substantive capacity shall qualify for pension if certain conditions are met, which includes that the autonomous body discharges the pension liability. In respect of the autonomous body under State Government, the condition for discharge of pension liability shall be binding on that autonomous body in accordance with the _______________ entered into by the Central Government with the concerned State Government.','Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981','reciprocal arrangement','Initial term & conditions of appointment before 31.12.2003','none of the above','reciprocal arrangement','Rule 14: The service rendered by a person in an autonomous body under the Central or State Government, having a non-contributory pension scheme, shall qualify for pension if they are subsequently appointed to a service or post in the Central Government. The service rendered in the autonomous body in an officiating, temporary, or substantive capacity shall qualify if certain conditions are met, including that the person\'s appointment in the Central Government is uninterrupted and that the autonomous body discharges the pension liability. \n Rule 14(2): The condition for discharge of pension liability by an autonomous body under the State Government having a non-contributory pension scheme similar to these rules shall be binding on that autonomous body in accordance with the reciprocal arrangement entered into by the Central Government with the concerned State Government. '],
['The "Casual Labourers (Grant of Temporary Status and Regularisation) Scheme of Government of India, 1993" allows ____________ of the service rendered by casual laborers on or before December 31, 2003, and subsequently regularized in Government service, to count as qualifying service for the purpose of pension rules.','25%','50%','75%','100%','50%','Rule 15- Service rendered in temporary status by casual labourers.- \nFifty percent of the service rendered in temporary status capacity by a Government servant, who was conferred temporary status on 31st December, 2003 and was subsequently regularised in Government service, in accordance with the "Casual Labourers (Grant of Temporary Status and Regularisation) Scheme of Government of India, 1993 notified by Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions (Department of Personnel and Training), shall count as qualifying service for the purpose of these rules.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct? \n1. Service on probation against a post if followed by confirmation in the same or another post shall count as qualifying service. \n2. Service as an apprentice shall also count as qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 16- Counting of service on probation- Service on probation against a post if followed by confirmation in the same or another post shall qualify. \nRule 17- Counting of service as an apprentice- Service as an apprentice shall not qualify, except in the case of Subordinate Accounts Service apprentice in the Indian Audit and Accounts Department or the Defence Accounts Department.'],
['A person initially engaged by the Government on a contract, who later gets appointed to a temporary, officiating, or substantive post in the same or another establishment without interruption of duty, can count the contract period as qualifying service if: ','the person is appointed on or before 31st December, 2003','If the person has exercised an option under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, to refund the Government\'s contribution to the Contributory Provident Fund with interest and any other compensation for that service.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 18- Counting of Service on contract: A person who was initially employed on a contract by the government and later appointed to a temporary or permanent position in the same or another establishment before December 31, 2003, without any break in service, and who has refunded the government contribution in the Contributory Provident Fund with interest as per the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, shall have the contract period count as qualifying service.'],
['What is required for a government servant who has retired on a compensation pension to have their former service counted as qualifying service upon re-employment?','They must have exercised an option under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, to cease drawing their pension and refunded or agreed to refund the pension already drawn, the commuted value of pension, and retirement gratuity including service gratuity, if any','They must have been re-employed and appointed after 31st December, 2003, and must not have received any pension or gratuity payments prior to their re-employment.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','They must have exercised an option under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, to cease drawing their pension and refunded or agreed to refund the pension already drawn, the commuted value of pension, and retirement gratuity including service gratuity, if any','Rule 19(1): A retired Government employee who is re-employed and appointed to a service or post to which these rules apply, and who chooses to stop drawing their pension and refunds any pension payments, commuted pension value, and retirement gratuity received, can count their former service as qualifying service. This applies to those re-employed or appointed before December 31st, 2003, and who made the appropriate option under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972.'],
['According to the rules for counting past service under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, which of the following is true?','The pension drawn prior to the date of re-employment was not required to be refunded.','The government servant must refund the pension amount that was ignored or not taken into account for their pay fixation.','The pension equivalent of gratuity and commuted pension, if taken into account for pay fixation, should be set off against the retirement gratuity and commuted value of pension. The balance amount, if any, must be refunded by the employee.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 19(2): In accordance with the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, for counting past service under the relevant rule: \n(i) the pension drawn prior to the date of re-employment was not required to be refunded. \n(ii) the element of pension which was ignored for fixation of his pay including the element of pension which was not taken into account for fixation of pay was to be refunded by the Government servant and \n(iii) the element of pension equivalent of gratuity including the element of commuted part of pension, if any, which was taken into account for fixation of his pay was to be set off against the amount of retirement gratuity and the commuted value of pension and the balance, if any, was to be refunded by him.'],
['With regard to the re-employed Government servants, if a Government servant opted for counting their former service, they were required to refund the gratuity received in respect of their earlier service in monthly instalments, not exceeding ___________.','Eighteen','Thirty Six','Forty-Eight','Sixty','Thirty Six','Rule 19(3): (3) A Government servant who opted for counting of his former service was required to refund the gratuity received in respect of his earlier service, in monthly instalments not exceeding thirty-six in number, the first instalment beginning from the month following the month in which he exercised the option. In such case, the right to count previous service as qualifying service shall not revive unless the whole amount has been refunded. '],
['With regard to the counting of pre-retirement civil service in the case of re-employed Government servants, which of the following is/are true?','To count former service as qualifying service, a government servant who received gratuity for earlier service must refund it in monthly installments within 36 months.','In such case, the right to count previous service as qualifying service shall not revive unless the whole amount has been refunded.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 19(3): (3) A Government servant who opted for counting of his former service was required to refund the gratuity received in respect of his earlier service, in monthly instalments not exceeding thirty-six in number, the first instalment beginning from the month following the month in which he exercised the option. In such case, the right to count previous service as qualifying service shall not revive unless the whole amount has been refunded. '],
['With regard to the re-employed Government servantsm, which of the following is/are true? ','A Government servant who opted for counting of his former service, must refund the gratuity received for his earlier service in the monthly installments not exceeding 36. ','If a Government servant dies before fully refunding the gratuity, the remaining amount will be adjusted against any death gratuity payable to their family.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 19(3): (3) A Government servant who opted for counting of his former service was required to refund the gratuity received in respect of his earlier service, in monthly instalments not exceeding thirty-six in number, the first instalment beginning from the month following the month in which he exercised the option. In such case, the right to count previous service as qualifying service shall not revive unless the whole amount has been refunded. \n Rule 19(4): In the case of a Government servant, who, having elected to refund the gratuity, dies before the entire amount is refunded, the amount of unrefunded gratuity shall be adjusted against the death gratuity which may become payable to his family.'],
['Which of the following statements is true in the case of a Government servant who opted to continue to draw the pension or retain the gratuity sanctioned for his earlier service, and in whose case his former service was not to be counted as qualifying service?','The pension or gratuity admissible for his subsequent service is calculated without taking into consideration the value of retirement benefits already granted to him for the previous service.','The service gratuity, or the capital value of the pension and retirement gratuity, if any, shall not be greater than the difference between the value of the pension and retirement gratuity that would be admissible at the time of the Government servant\'s final retirement if the two periods of service were combined and the value of retirement benefits already granted to him for the previous service.','The Government servant is required to refund the entire amount of retirement benefits already granted to him for the previous service before he can draw the pension or gratuity for his subsequent service.','The Government servant\'s subsequent service will not be considered for calculating his pension or gratuity, regardless of whether he opted to count his previous service as qualifying service or not.','The service gratuity, or the capital value of the pension and retirement gratuity, if any, shall not be greater than the difference between the value of the pension and retirement gratuity that would be admissible at the time of the Government servant\'s final retirement if the two periods of service were combined and the value of retirement benefits already granted to him for the previous service.','Rule 19(5): In the case of a Government servant who opted to continue to draw the pension or retain the gratuity sanctioned for his earlier service, and in whose case his former service was not to be counted as qualifying service, the pension or gratuity admissible for his subsequent service is subject to the limitation that service gratuity, or the capital value of the pension and retirement gratuity, if any, shall not be greater than the difference between the value of the pension and retirement gratuity, if any, that would be admissible at the time of the Government ervant\'s final retirement if the two periods of service were combined and the value of retirement benefits already granted to him for the previous service.'],

['Which of the following is required for a government servant who has rendered military service and was re-employed in a civil service or post before 31st December 2003 to count their previous military service as qualifying service according to the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972?','They must have refunded or agreed to refund the pension already drawn.','They must have refunded or agreed to refund the value received for the commutation of a part of military pension','They must have refunded or agreed to refund the amount of retirement gratuity including service gratuity','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 20-Counting of military service rendered before civil employment- \n(1) A Government servant, who after having rendered military service, was re-employed in a civil service or post on or before 31st December, 2003 and who on such reemployment, in accordance with an option exercised under the Central Civil Services (Pension) Rules, 1972, ceased to draw his pension and refunded or agreed to refund- \n(i) the pension already drawn; and \n(ii) the value received for the commutation of a part of military pension; and \n(iii) the amount of retirement gratuity including service gratuity, if any; shall count previous military service, as qualifying service.'],
['If a government servant had rendered military service after joining that service after 31st December 2003 and is subsequently re-employed in a civil service or post, they can continue to draw their military pension or retain gratuity received on discharge from military service. However, on re-employment, they will be covered by the rules governing the _________________.','Old Pension System','National Pension System','Pension Scheme under EPFO','Contributory Provident Fund Rules (India ), 1962','National Pension System','A Government servant, who had rendered military service after joining that service after 31st December, 2003, shall, on re-employment in a civil service or post, continue to draw the military pension or retain gratuity received on discharge from military service and on re-employment in a civil service or post, he shall be covered by the rules governing the National Pension System.'],
['With regard to the pension and gratuity for the service rendered after re-employment in civil service or post by a government servant who has previously rendered military service, select the correct statement:','There is no limitation on the pension and gratuity for service rendered after re-employment in civil service or post by a government servant who previously served in the military.','The service gratuity or capital value of their pension and retirement gratuity cannot exceed the difference between the value of their pension and retirement gratuity if the two periods of service were combined at the time of their final retirement and the retirement benefits already granted for their previous service.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','There is no limitation on the pension and gratuity for service rendered after re-employment in civil service or post by a government servant who previously served in the military.','Rule 20 (5)- The pension and gratuity for the service rendered after re-employment in civil service or post shall not be subject to any limitation with reference to the pension and gratuity drawn by the Government servant in respect of the military service.'],
['When can extraordinary leave other than that granted on medical certificate be allowed to count as qualifying service?','When it\'s granted to appear for exams','When it\'s granted for civil commotion or for higher scientific and technical studies','When it\'s granted for a religious pilgrimage','The HoD decides on case to case basis','When it\'s granted for civil commotion or for higher scientific and technical studies','Rule 21- Counting of periods spent on leave- \nAll leave during service for which leave salary is payable and all extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate shall count as qualifying service: \nProvided that in the case of extraordinary leave other than extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate, the appointing authority may, at the time of granting such leave, allow the period of that leave to count as qualifying service if such leave is granted to a Government servant,- \n(i) due to his inability to join or re-join duty on account of civil commotion; or \n(ii) for prosecuting higher scientific and technical studies. \n Explanation: This rule states that if a government servant takes extraordinary leave, except for medical reasons, a note should be made in the service book that the period of leave will not be considered as qualifying service. This entry should be made at the time of granting the leave, but it can also be made later, but not later than six months before the retirement of the government servant. If no such entry is made, the extraordinary leave will be considered as qualifying service.'],
['Which of the following statement(s) is/are correct? ','All leave during service for which leave salary is payable and all extraordinary leave shall count as qualifying service.','If a government servant takes extraordinary leave (other than on medical grounds), the appointing authority cannot allow it to count as qualifying service under any circumstances.','At the time of granting EOL (without medical certificate), a clear entry must be made in the service book stating that the period of EOL will not be counted as qualifying service. If such an entry is not made, the period of extraordinary leave will be treated as qualifying service.','None of the above','At the time of granting EOL (without medical certificate), a clear entry must be made in the service book stating that the period of EOL will not be counted as qualifying service. If such an entry is not made, the period of extraordinary leave will be treated as qualifying service.','Rule 21- Counting of periods spent on leave- \nAll leave during service for which leave salary is payable and all extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate shall count as qualifying service: \nProvided that in the case of extraordinary leave other than extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate, the appointing authority may, at the time of granting such leave, allow the period of that leave to count as qualifying service if such leave is granted to a Government servant,- \n(i) due to his inability to join or re-join duty on account of civil commotion; or \n(ii) for prosecuting higher scientific and technical studies. \n Explanation: This rule states that if a government servant takes extraordinary leave, except for medical reasons, a note should be made in the service book that the period of leave will not be considered as qualifying service. This entry should be made at the time of granting the leave, but it can also be made later, but not later than six months before the retirement of the government servant. If no such entry is made, the extraordinary leave will be considered as qualifying service.'],
['What is the time limit within which a definite entry stating that the period of extraordinary leave shall not be treated as qualifying service should be made in the service book of a Government servant?','Within 30 days of granting extraordinary leave.','Not later than six months before the date of retirement of the Government servant on superannuation.','Within 30 days of resuming duty after extraordinary leave.','Within 1 year of granting Extraordinary Leave','Not later than six months before the date of retirement of the Government servant on superannuation.','Rule 21- Counting of periods spent on leave- \nAll leave during service for which leave salary is payable and all extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate shall count as qualifying service: \nProvided that in the case of extraordinary leave other than extraordinary leave granted on medical certificate, the appointing authority may, at the time of granting such leave, allow the period of that leave to count as qualifying service if such leave is granted to a Government servant,- \n(i) due to his inability to join or re-join duty on account of civil commotion; or \n(ii) for prosecuting higher scientific and technical studies. \n Explanation: This rule states that if a government servant takes extraordinary leave, except for medical reasons, a note should be made in the service book that the period of leave will not be considered as qualifying service. This entry should be made at the time of granting the leave, but it can also be made later, but not later than six months before the retirement of the government servant. If no such entry is made, the extraordinary leave will be considered as qualifying service.'],
['Which of the following statement(s) is/are correct? \n1. The Government may decide whether the time spent under training before appointment to service under that Government shall be counted as qualifying service. \n2. If counted, interruption due to training and regular appointment being at different stations shall be counted as qualifying service, not exceeding the joining time permissible under transfer rules.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 22: Counting of periods spent on training: \nIf a government servant received pay during departmental training before their appointment to a Group C post, that period of training will count as qualifying service. \nIn cases where this condition is not met, the government has the authority to decide whether the time spent under training before appointment to service will be counted as qualifying service. \nIf counted, interruption due to training and regular appointment being at different stations shall be counted as qualifying service, not exceeding the joining time permissible under transfer rules. \nIf the period of interruption is in excess of joining time due to administrative reasons, it can be regularised by granting leave or extraordinary leave, and such period of interruption shall be counted as qualifying service.'],
['When the training time before appointment counts as qualifying service, interruptions due to training and joining at different stations within the transfer rules\' time limit will also count as qualifying service. What happens if the period of interruption is in excess of joining time?','If the period of interruption is in excess of joining time due to administrative reasons, it can be regularised by granting leave or extraordinary leave by HoD.','Such period of interruption shall be counted as qualifying service.','The period of interruption regularised by grant of extraordinary leave shall be counted as qualifying service.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 22: Counting of periods spent on training: \nIf a government servant received pay during departmental training before their appointment to a Group C post, that period of training will count as qualifying service. \nIn cases where this condition is not met, the government has the authority to decide whether the time spent under training before appointment to service will be counted as qualifying service. \nIf counted, interruption due to training and regular appointment being at different stations shall be counted as qualifying service, not exceeding the joining time permissible under transfer rules. \nIf the period of interruption is in excess of joining time due to administrative reasons, it can be regularised by granting leave or extraordinary leave, and such period of interruption shall be counted as qualifying service.'],
['Which of the following statement(s) is/are correct? \n1. The period of suspension will count as qualifying service only if the inquiry finds the government servant fully exonerated. \n2. Fifty percent period of suspension will count as qualifying service if only minor penalty imposed and the suspension is held to be wholly unjustified. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 23- Counting of periods of suspension- \n(1) Time passed by a Government servant under suspension pending inquiry into conduct shall be counted as qualifying service where, on conclusion of such inquiry, he has been fully exonerated or only a minor penalty is imposed and the suspension is held to be wholly unjustified. \n(2) In cases not covered under sub-rule (1), the period of suspension shall not count unless the authority competent to pass orders under the rule governing such cases expressly declares at the time that it shall count to such extent as the Competent Authority may declare. \n(3) In all cases of suspension, the competent authority shall pass an order specifying the extent to which, if any, the period of suspension shall count as qualifying service and a definite entry shall be made in the service book of the Government servant in this regard'],
['What must be done by the competent authority in all cases of suspension?','The competent authority must pass an order specifying the extent to which, if any, the period of suspension shall count as qualifying service.','a definite entry shall be made in the service book of the Government servant in this regard.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 23- Counting of periods of suspension- \n(1) Time passed by a Government servant under suspension pending inquiry into conduct shall be counted as qualifying service where, on conclusion of such inquiry, he has been fully exonerated or only a minor penalty is imposed and the suspension is held to be wholly unjustified. \n(2) In cases not covered under sub-rule (1), the period of suspension shall not count unless the authority competent to pass orders under the rule governing such cases expressly declares at the time that it shall count to such extent as the Competent Authority may declare. \n(3) In all cases of suspension, the competent authority shall pass an order specifying the extent to which, if any, the period of suspension shall count as qualifying service and a definite entry shall be made in the service book of the Government servant in this regard'],
['Under what circumstances will the time passed by a Government servant under suspension be counted as qualifying service?','If only a minor penalty is imposed and the suspension is held to be wholly unjustified.','If the Govt. Servant is fully exonerated on conclusion of inquiry.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 23- Counting of periods of suspension- \n(1) Time passed by a Government servant under suspension pending inquiry into conduct shall be counted as qualifying service where, on conclusion of such inquiry, he has been fully exonerated or only a minor penalty is imposed and the suspension is held to be wholly unjustified. \n(2) In cases not covered under sub-rule (1), the period of suspension shall not count unless the authority competent to pass orders under the rule governing such cases expressly declares at the time that it shall count to such extent as the Competent Authority may declare. \n(3) In all cases of suspension, the competent authority shall pass an order specifying the extent to which, if any, the period of suspension shall count as qualifying service and a definite entry shall be made in the service book of the Government servant in this regard'],
['If a Government servant is dismissed or removed from a service or post, it will result in:','recovery of pay and allowances from Govt. Servant','Forfeiture of past service','Botha (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Forfeiture of past service','Rule 24: Dismissal or removal of a Government servant from a service or post shall entail forfeiture of his past service.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct? \n1. A Government servant who was dismissed, removed or compulsorily retired from service, and is subsequently reinstated on appeal or review, is entitled to count his past service as qualifying service. \n2. The period of interruption in service between the date of dismissal or removal and the date of reinstatement shall count as qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 25- Counting of past service on reinstatement- \n(1) A Government servant who was dismissed, removed or compulsorily retired from service, and is subsequently reinstated on appeal or review, is entitled to count his past service as qualifying service. \n(2) The period of interruption in service between the date of dismissal, removal or compulsory retirement, as the case may be, and the date of reinstatement, and the period of suspension, if any, shall not count as qualifying service unless regularized as duty or leave by a specific order of the authority which passed the order of reinstatement.'],
['What are the conditions for a government servant to withdraw their resignation in the public interest?','The resignation was tendered for compelling reasons that did not reflect on the person\'s integrity, efficiency, or conduct and the request to withdraw the resignation is due to a material change in circumstances.','The person\'s conduct during the period between the resignation becoming effective and the request to withdraw is not improper and the post vacated by the person or a comparable post is available.','The period of absence from duty between the resignation becoming effective and the request to withdraw is no more than 90 days.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 26(5)- The appointing authority may permit a person to withdraw his resignation in the public interest on the following conditions, namely :- \n(i) that the resignation was tendered by the Government servant for some compelling reasons which did not involve any reflection on his integrity, efficiency or conduct and the request for withdrawal of the resignation has been made as a result of a material change in the circumstances which originally compelled him to tender the resignation; \n(ii) that during the period intervening between the date on which the resignation became effective and the date from which the request for withdrawal was made, the conduct of the person concerned was in no way improper; \n(iii) that the period of absence from duty between the date on which the resignation became effective and the date on which the person applies for permission to withdraw the resignation is not more than ninety days; \n(iv) that the post, which was vacated by the Government servant on the acceptance of his resignation or any other comparable post, is available.'],
['Appointing authority cannot accept request for withdrawal of resignation in certain cases. These case(s) include:','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a private commercial company.','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a corporation or company owned or controlled by the government','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a body controlled or financed by the government.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 26(6): Request for withdrawal of a resignation shall not be accepted by the appointing authority where a Government servant resigns his service or post with a view to taking up an appointment in or under a private commercial company or in or under a corporation or company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Government or in or under a body controlled or financed by the Government.'],
['When an order is passed by the appointing authority allowing a person to withdraw his resignation and to resume duty, then: \n1. The order shall be deemed to include the condonation of interruption in service. \n2. The period of such interruption shall count as qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 26(7) When an order is passed by the appointing authority allowing a person to withdraw his resignation and to resume duty, the order shall be deemed to include the condonation of interruption in service but the period of interruption shall not count as qualifying service.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. Resignation does not result in forfeiture of past service if it is taken up with permission to another position under the government. \n2. Leave or formal condonation will cover interruptions in service due to two appointments at different stations, as long as the period does not exceed the permitted joining time under transfer rules.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 26(1): Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \nrule 26(2) A resignation shall not entail forfeiture of past service if it has been submitted to take up, with proper permission, another appointment, whether temporary or permanent, under the Government where service qualifies. \nRule 26(3) The order accepting the resignation should clearly indicate that the Government servant has resigned to join another appointment with proper permission and a specific entry to this effect shall also be made by the Head of Office in the service book of the Government servant. \nRule 26(4) Interruption in service in a case falling under sub-rule (2), due to the two appointments being at different stations, not exceeding the joining time permissible under the rules of transfer, shall be covered by grant of leave of any kind due to the Government servant on the date of relief or by formal condonation to the extent to which the period is not covered by leave due to him.'],
['Which of the following circumstances would result in forfeiture of a government servant\'s past service?','Suspension followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension.','Unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence until the post of absentee is not filled substantively.','Transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government, ordered by a competent authority in the public interest.','Resignation from a service or a post.','Resignation from a service or a post.','Rule 26- Forfeiture of service on resignation.- (1) Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \n Rule 27(1) An interruption in the service of a Government servant entails forfeiture of his past service, except in the following cases, namely:- \n(a) authorised leave of absence; \n(b) unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence so long as the post of absentee is not filled substantively; \n(c) suspension, where it is immediately followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the Government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension; \n(d) transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government if such transfer has been ordered by a competent authority in the public interest; \n(e) joining time while on transfer from one post to another. \nRule 27(2) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), the appointing authority may, by order, commute retrospectively the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave.'],
['Select the correct code from below: \n1. The appointing authority may commute the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave. \n2. if a Government servant is absent without authorization after his authorized leave period has ended, but the post he was occupying has not been filled, his past service will be forfeited if such absence exceeds 180 days.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 26- Forfeiture of service on resignation.- (1) Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \n Rule 27(1) An interruption in the service of a Government servant entails forfeiture of his past service, except in the following cases, namely:- \n(a) authorised leave of absence; \n(b) unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence so long as the post of absentee is not filled substantively; \n(c) suspension, where it is immediately followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the Government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension; \n(d) transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government if such transfer has been ordered by a competent authority in the public interest; \n(e) joining time while on transfer from one post to another. \nRule 27(2) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), the appointing authority may, by order, commute retrospectively the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. If there is no mention in the service book, any gap between two spells of civil service rendered by a government servant will be automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service will be considered as qualifying service. \n2. This does not apply to civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates under the government.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service- \n(1) In the absence of a specific indication to the contrary in the service book, an interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant under Government including civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service treated as qualifying service.'],
['Interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service as qualifying service except in which of the following case(s):','Resignation','Removal from Service or Dismissal','For participation in a strike','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service- \n(1) In the absence of a specific indication to the contrary in the service book, an interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant under Government including civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service treated as qualifying service. \n(2) Nothing in sub-rule (1) shall apply to interruption caused by resignation, dismissal or removal from service or for participation in a strike.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. Interruption between two spells of civil service is automatically condoned if not indicated otherwise in service book and exceptions include interruptions due to resignation, dismissal, removal from service, or participation in a strike. \n2. The appointing authority may consider condonation and treat the interruption period as qualifying. \n3. Appointing authority may refuse condonation in exceptional and grave circumstances, but the government servant must be given a chance to be heard before the decision.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','2 and 3 only','All of the above','1 and 3 only','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service: \nInterruption between two spells of civil service is automatically condoned if not indicated otherwise in the service book. \nExceptions include interruptions due to resignation, dismissal, removal from service, or participation in a strike.\nThe interrupted period does not count as qualifying service. \nThe appointing authority may consider condonation and treat the pre-interruption service as qualifying. \nThe appointing authority may decline condonation in exceptional and grave circumstances.\n The government servant must be given a reasonable opportunity to be heard before any decision is made against condonation.'],
['Can a Government servant count their foreign service to UN bodies as qualifying for pension if they do not pay pension contributions for it?','Yes','No','Only if they are deputed to the United Nations Secretariat','Only if they are deputed to the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development.','No','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['If a Government servant opts not to pay pension contributions for their foreign service in International Organization, what happens to the contributions, if any, already paid by the Government servant?','They are used to fund other pension schemes.','They are refunded to the Govt. Servant','They are paid to the Govt. Servant on their return from such service.','None of the above','They are refunded to the Govt. Servant','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['Which of the following options is available to a Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to Asian Development Bank?','To pay pension contributions in respect of foreign service and count it as qualifying for pension under these rules.','To not pay pension contributions in respect of foreign service and not count it as qualifying for pension under these rules.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['The ______________, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation.','Head of Department','Head of Office','Drawing and Disbursing Officer','Internal Audit Wing','Head of Office','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on which of the following occasions? \n1. After completing 18 years of service. \n2. When there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \n3. After completing 25 years of service.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','1 and 2 only','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['In the context of Pension Rules, what is the purpose of Format 4?','It indicates the period counted as non-qualifying.','To communicate to the Government servant the period of qualifying service determined.','It is the Indemnity Bond to be furnished by a claimant of Gratuity or Family Pension.','It is an Indemnity Bond by Guardian for payment of gratuity to minor.','To communicate to the Government servant the period of qualifying service determined.','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['The Head of Office shall follow the procedure provided in clause (a) of sub-rule (1) of _________ for the verification of service in consultation with Accounts Officer.','Rule 56','Rule 57','Rule 58','Rule 59','Rule 57','Rule 30: The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. The Head of Office shall follow the procedure provided in clause (a) of sub-rule (1) of rule 57 for the verification of service.'],
['Under which of the following circumstance(s), the verification of service may be done: ','When a Government servant is transferred to another department from a temporary department.',' On account of the closure of the department he had been previously serving.','If the post he held had been declared surplus.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(3): Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), where a Government servant is transferred to another department from a temporary department or on account of the closure of the department he had been previously serving or because the post he held had been declared surplus, the verification of his service may be done whenever such event occurs. '],
['In what circumstances can the verification of service be reopened under the Pension Rules?','In case of foreign service to Internationa Organization like IMF, World Bank etc.','On the request of the Govt. Servant citing valid grounds for such reverification.','When necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.','All of the above','When necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(4) The verification done under this rule shall be treated as final and shall not be reopened except when necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.'],
['A report must be submitted to the Secretary of the Administrative Ministry or Department by ______________ every year containing details of government servants who needed a certificate of qualifying service during the previous year, those who were issued with the certificate, and the reasons why the certificate was not issued in the remaining cases.','January 31st','March 31st','September 30th','June 30th','January 31st','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(5) By 31st January of each year, a report shall be submitted to the Secretary of the Administrative Ministry or Department giving the details of the Government servants who were required to be issued a certificate of qualifying service during the previous calendar year under sub-rule (1), the details of the Government servants who have actually been issued the said certificate during the said period and the reasons for not issuing the said certificate in the remaining cases.'],
['In the context of emoluments for retirement benefits, which of the following does NOT form part of a Government servant\'s emoluments?','Basic pay as defined in Fundamental Rules, 1922','Non-practising allowance granted to a medical officer in lieu of private practice','Stagnation increment','Any increase in pay that is not actually drawn except in special case.','Any increase in pay that is not actually drawn except in special case.','Rule 31- Emoluments: \nThe term \'emoluments\' refers to a Government servant\'s basic pay at the time of retirement or death, including non-practising allowance given to medical officers in lieu of private practice. Stagnation increment will also be considered as emoluments for retirement benefits. If a Government servant was on leave or suspended before retirement or death, the emoluments he would have received if he had not been absent or suspended will be included. Any increase in pay that was not actually received will not be considered as emoluments [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (5) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (10) or sub-rule (11)].'],
['Which of the following is/are NOT correct: \n1. If a government servant was on leave (including EOL on medical certificate) immediately before his retirement or death, the emoluments he would have drawn if he were not absent would be considered for calculating retirement benefits. \n2. Increment earned but not drawn during leave before retirement or death shall be part of emoluments.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Rule 31(2): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on extraordinary leave on medical certificate or, having been suspended, had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall form part of his emoluments. \nRule 31(5) Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service, was on leave, and earned an increment which was not withheld, such increment, though not actually drawn, shall form part of his emoluments.'],
['Under what condition the benefit of emoluments is given to a Government servant who proceeds on leave after holding a higher appointment in an officiating or temporary capacity before retirement or death while in service?','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given without any condition.','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if the government servant has completed a minimum tenure in that position.','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if it is certified that the government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for the leave.','No benefit is applicable to the government servant in such cases and retirement benefits are ','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if it is certified that the government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for the leave.','Rule 31(3): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had proceeded on leave for which leave salary is payable after having held a higher appointment whether in an officiating or temporary capacity, the benefit of emoluments drawn in such higher appointment shall be given only if it is certified that the Government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for his proceeding on leave.'],
['Which of the following applies to a Government servant who had been under suspension immediately before his retirement or death while in service?','The emoluments earned during the period of suspension are included in his retirement benefits.','The emoluments earned immediately before being placed under suspension will be considered part of their total emoluments for retirement benefits.','The Government servant is not eligible for any retirement benefits.','None of the above','The emoluments earned immediately before being placed under suspension will be considered part of their total emoluments for retirement benefits.','Rule 31(4): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave or had been under suspension, the period whereof does not count as service, the emoluments which he drew immediately before proceeding on such leave or being placed under suspension shall form part of his emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding pay drawn by a government servant while on deputation to an ex-cadre post in the same or some other department of the government or to the Armed Forces of India?','The pay received by a government servant while on such deputation will not be considered as emoluments.','if the government servant goes on leave after the completion of the deputation period, the pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments.','The pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments during the whole period of deputation','None of the above ','if the government servant goes on leave after the completion of the deputation period, the pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(6): Pay drawn by a Government servant while on deputation to an ex-cadre post in the same or some other Department of the Government or to the Armed Forces of India shall be treated as emoluments: Provided that in the case of a Government servant while on leave after release from the ex-cadre post on completion of the period of deputation, the pay which he would have drawn in the parent department had he not been on leave shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statement is true regarding the pay of a government servant on deputation to a state government or foreign service?','The pay drawn by the government servant on such deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating retirement benefits.','The pay that the Govt. Servant would have earned if they had not been on deputation will be considered as emoluments.','It depends on the option exercised by the Govt. Servant.','The Terms & Conditions of such deputation will regulate and define the emoluments.','The pay that the Govt. Servant would have earned if they had not been on deputation will be considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(7): Pay drawn by a Government servant while on deputation to a State Government or while on foreign service shall not be treated as emoluments, but the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deputation to the State Government or on foreign service shall alone be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the treatment of emoluments for pensioners who are re-employed in government service and opt to retain their pension from earlier service?','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is not considered as emoluments.','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is considered as emoluments.','The emoluments drawn during the earlier service are not taken into account for pension calculation.','None of the above','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(8): Where a pensioner who is re-employed in Government service elected to retain his pension for earlier service and whose pay on re-employment had been reduced by an amount not exceeding his pension, the element of pension by which his pay is reduced shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding the treatment of emoluments for government servants transferred to a public sector undertaking or autonomous body after the conversion of their department?','The emoluments drawn under the new organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','The emoluments drawn under the previous organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','The employee\'s pension benefits will be forfeited upon transfer to the new organization.','None of the above','The emoluments drawn under the previous organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','Rule 31(9) When a Government servant has been transferred to a public sector undertaking or an autonomous body consequent on the conversion of a Department of the Government into such public sector undertaking or autonomous body and the Government servant so transferred opts to retain the pensionary benefits under the rules of the Government, the emoluments drawn under the public sector undertaking or autonomous body shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['In what circumstance will the notional pay be treated as emoluments for a retired government servant?','When the pay scale of the employee\'s previous post is increased retrospectively irrespective of the date when they were in service.',' When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)',' When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','Rule 31(10): The treatment of notional pay as emoluments for government servants who have retired but whose pay is notionally increased with retrospective effect. This includes two scenarios: \n(i) when the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively, and the pensioner\'s pay in the higher pay scale is fixed on a notional basis; \n(ii) when the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.'],
['What are the conditions for the treatment of increased notional pay as emoluments for a retired government servant? \n1. When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order. \n2. The benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 31(10): The treatment of notional pay as emoluments for government servants who have retired but whose pay is notionally increased with retrospective effect. This includes two scenarios: \n(i) when the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively, and the pensioner\'s pay in the higher pay scale is fixed on a notional basis; \n(ii) when the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.'],
['What happens when a Govt. servant dies during the currency of the penalty that reduces their pay only until the expiry of the penalty?','The penalty will continue to affect the government servant\'s pay even after their death.','The notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty are treated as emoluments.','The order imposing the said penalty will have specific mention in this regard.','None of the above','The notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty are treated as emoluments.','Rule 31(11): Where a Government servant dies during the currency of a penalty which has the effect of reducing his pay only during the currency of that penalty and on expiry of which he would have regained the pay admissible to him without any impact of the said penalty, the notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty shall be treated as emoluments'],
['Average emoluments shall be determined with reference to the emoluments drawn by a Government servant during the last ___________________ of his service.','Six months','Ten months','Twelve months','Eighteen months','Ten months','Rule 32: Average emoluments shall be determined with reference to the emoluments drawn by a Government servant during the last ten months of his service.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the calculation of average emoluments for a government servant who is absent from duty for which leave salary is payable or suspended (followed by reinstatement) during the last ten months of their service?','The emoluments they actually receive during this time will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The emoluments they would have received if they were not absent or suspended will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Any increase in pay during this time will be included in their emoluments, even if it was not actually received.','None of the above','The emoluments they would have received if they were not absent or suspended will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Rule 32(2): In case during the last ten months of his service a Government servant had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate or having been suspended had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments : \nProvided that any increase in pay [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (4) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (5) or sub-rule (6)] which is not actually drawn shall not form part of his emoluments.'],
['The average emoluments in respect of a Govt. Servant who is on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate during the last 10 months of service will be :','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','None of the above','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Rule 32(2): In case during the last ten months of his service a Government servant had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate or having been suspended had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments : \nProvided that any increase in pay [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (4) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (5) or sub-rule (6)] which is not actually drawn shall not form part of his emoluments.'],
['The average emoluments in respect of a Govt. Servant who is on Extraordinary leave during the last 10 months of service will be :','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','None of the above','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','Rule 32(3): In case during the last ten months of his service, a Government servant had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave, or had been under suspension the period whereof does not count as service, the aforesaid period of leave or suspension shall be disregarded in the calculation of the average emoluments and equal period before the ten months shall be included. In order that the fractions of a month, when added, worked out to one full month, a month for this purpose shall be reckoned as consisting of thirty days. \nIllustration: A Government servant retires on 16th July, 2019. The last ten months comprise nine full months and fractions of fourteen days of September, 2018 and sixteen days of July, 2019. The emoluments for fractional periods shall be computed by multiplying the emolument by the factor 14/30 and 16/30 irrespective of the number of days in the month. This formula shall also apply in the case of the month of February, irrespective of whether the month has twenty eight days or twenty nine days.'],
['If a Government servant was under suspension during the last ten months of their service, and if this period does not count towards their service then the Average emoluments will be:','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not under suspension will be used to determine their average emoluments.','the period of suspension will be excluded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten-month period will be included in the calculation','None of the above','the period of suspension will be excluded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten-month period will be included in the calculation','Rule 32(3): In case during the last ten months of his service, a Government servant had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave, or had been under suspension the period whereof does not count as service, the aforesaid period of leave or suspension shall be disregarded in the calculation of the average emoluments and equal period before the ten months shall be included. In order that the fractions of a month, when added, worked out to one full month, a month for this purpose shall be reckoned as consisting of thirty days. \nIllustration: A Government servant retires on 16th July, 2019. The last ten months comprise nine full months and fractions of fourteen days of September, 2018 and sixteen days of July, 2019. The emoluments for fractional periods shall be computed by multiplying the emolument by the factor 14/30 and 16/30 irrespective of the number of days in the month. This formula shall also apply in the case of the month of February, irrespective of whether the month has twenty eight days or twenty nine days.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the inclusion of increments in the average emoluments for pension calculations?','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is not included','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is included, even if it was not actually received','Only increments earned during active service are included','None of the above','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is included, even if it was not actually received','Rule 32(4): (4) In the case of a Government servant who was on leave during the last ten months of his service and earned an increment, which was not withheld, such increment though not actually drawn shall be included in the average emoluments.'],
['When is the notional pay increase of a Government servant, with retrospective effect during the last ten months of their service after retirement, taken into account for calculating their average emoluments?','if the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively.','if the pensioner is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a review Departmental Promotion Committee, or on exoneration in any departmental proceedings, or in compliance with a court order.','if the benefit of pay fixation is allowed on a notional basis from the date of such promotion.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 32(4): If a Government servant was on leave during the last ten months of their service and earned an increment, which was not withheld, then the increment will be included in the average emoluments even if it was not actually received. \nRule 32(5): If the pay of a Government servant is increased with retrospective effect during the last ten months of their service after retirement, then the notional pay will be taken into account for determining the average emoluments. This applies if the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively or if the pensioner is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a review Departmental Promotion Committee, or on exoneration in any departmental proceedings, or in compliance with a court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed on a notional basis from the date of such promotion.'],
['What happens to average emoluments when a Govt. servant dies during the currency of the penalty that reduces their pay only until the expiry of the penalty?','The penalty will continue to affect the government servant\'s average emoluments even after their death.','The notional pay during the last ten months of service, without the impact of the penalty, will be considered for calculating their average emoluments.','The order imposing the said penalty will have specific mention in this regard.','None of the above','The notional pay during the last ten months of service, without the impact of the penalty, will be considered for calculating their average emoluments.','Rule 32(6): Where a Government servant dies during the currency of a penalty which has the effect of reducing his pay only during the currency of that penalty and on expiry of which he would have regained the pay admissible to him without any impact of the said penalty, the notional pay during the last ten months of his service ignoring the effect of such penalty shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments.'],
['When a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation, they shall be granted a superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as per the provisions of _______________.','Rule 42','Rule 43','Rule 44','Rule 45','Rule 44','Rule 33- Superannuation pension or service gratuity.- A superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as the case may be, shall be granted in accordance with rule 44 to a Government servant who is retired on his attaining the age of superannuation or, if the service of the Government servant has been extended beyond superannuation, on expiry of such period of extension of service beyond the age of superannuation.'],
['Which of the following is true about the grant of superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity to a Government servant?','It is only granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation','It is only granted when a Government servant\'s service is extended beyond the age of superannuation.','It is granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation','None of the above','It is granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation','Rule 33- Superannuation pension or service gratuity.- A superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as the case may be, shall be granted in accordance with rule 44 to a Government servant who is retired on his attaining the age of superannuation or, if the service of the Government servant has been extended beyond superannuation, on expiry of such period of extension of service beyond the age of superannuation.'],
['A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee: \n1. who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of Fundamental Rule or rule 56 of CCS Pension Rules, 2021. \n2. who is retired by the Government, before attaining the age of superannuation, in accordance with the provisions of rule 42 of these rules or rule 56 of the Fundamental Rules. \n3. who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','None of the above','2 and 3 only','Rule 34- Retiring pension or service gratuity- A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of these rules or rule 56 of Fundamental rules. The pension or gratuity is also given to an employee who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme. The government may retire an employee before reaching the age of superannuation in accordance with rule 42 of these rules or Fundamental rule 56. The specific rules governing the awarding of the pension or gratuity are detailed in rule 44.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme for government servants who are declared surplus?','Employees who opt for the scheme are not eligible for any retirement gratuity.','All such Govt. Servant are entitled to ex-gratia payment.','Employees who opt for the scheme are entitled to a retiring pension or service gratuity in accordance with rule 44.','The scheme is only available to employees who retire on their own volition.','Employees who opt for the scheme are entitled to a retiring pension or service gratuity in accordance with rule 44.','"Rule 34- Retiring pension or service gratuity- A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of these rules or rule 56 of Fundamental rules. The pension or gratuity is also given to an employee who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme. The government may retire an employee before reaching the age of superannuation in accordance with rule 42 of these rules or Fundamental rule 56. The specific rules governing the awarding of the pension or gratuity are detailed in rule 44. \n Rule 34(2): If a permanent government servant is declared surplus to the establishment and chooses to opt for the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme, they will be entitled to an ex-gratia payment according to the scheme. This will be in addition to the retiring pension or service gratuity awarded in accordance with rule 44, as well as the retirement gratuity under rule 45.'],
['What happens when a government servant is absorbed into a service or post in a state government?','They are not eligible for pension or gratuity.','They will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption.','They will be eligible for pension or gratuity, but not retirement gratuity.','They will be eligible for retirement gratuity, but not pension or gratuity.','They will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45: \nProvided that on retirement from the State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in the State Government shall not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in the Central Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from the State Government.'],
['What is the limit on the total amount of gratuity for a government servant who has been absorbed into a service or post in a state government?','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the state government service.','There is no limit on the total amount of gratuity.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on the same pay as they did when retiring from the state government.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on a pay which is 1 stage lower than what they received when retiring from the state government.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on the same pay as they did when retiring from the state government.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45: \nProvided that on retirement from the State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in the State Government shall not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in the Central Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from the State Government.'],
['What is the date of absorption for a government employee who joins a state government?','The date of acceptance of their resignation from the central government service.','The date on which they submit their resignation to the central government.','The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis.','The date on which their deputation to the state government begins.','The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- \n35(1): If a government servant is allowed to be absorbed into a service or post in a state government, they will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption. They will be eligible for pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on their qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45. \n 35(2): The date of absorption for a government employee who joins a state government shall be: \n(i) The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis. Immediate absorption refers to the acceptance of a technical resignation from the central government service to take up an appointment in the state government for which they had applied with proper permission. \n(ii) The date from which their unqualified resignation is accepted by the central government if they initially join the state government on deputation.'],
['When a government employee joins the state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in _____________ indicating the period within which they must join the state government.','Format 3','Format 4','Format 5','Format 6','Format 5','Rule 35(3): When a government employee joins a state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in Format 5 indicating the period within which they must join the state government. This period can be extended by the relieving authority if there are reasons beyond the control of the government servant. \nRule 35(4): The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave or extraordinary leave.'],
['When a Government employee joins a State Government on immediate absorption, which of the following is applicable?','The relieving order will be issued in Format 7 indicating the period within which they must join the state government.','This period may be extended by the relieving authority on specific request of the Servant.','The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave due and admissible or extraordinary leave, if no leave is due.','if the joining is not within the specified period then the excess duration will be treated as interruption in service and it won\'t qualify. ','The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave due and admissible or extraordinary leave, if no leave is due.','Rule 35(3): When a government employee joins a state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in Format 5 indicating the period within which they must join the state government. This period can be extended by the relieving authority if there are reasons beyond the control of the government servant. \nRule 35(4): The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave or extraordinary leave.'],
['Which of the following statement is accurate with regard to accepting the resignation of a government servant who joins a state government on immediate absorption basis?','The resignation is accepted from the same date as the date of joining the state government.','The resignation is accepted from the date preceding the date of joining the state government.','The resignation is not required to be accepted.','None of the above','The resignation is accepted from the date preceding the date of joining the state government.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- \n35(1): If a government servant is allowed to be absorbed into a service or post in a state government, they will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption. \nRule 35(5): The relieving authority, before processing the case for sanction of retirement benefits, will ascertain the date of joining by the Government servant in the State Government and accept the resignation of the Government servant from the date preceding the date of joining.'],
['What options are available to a Government servant who is absorbed by a State Government and a similar pension scheme exists in that State Government?','To receive only the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government.','To count only the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','To either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government or count the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','No options are applicable in this case and the Govt. Servant is deemed to have retired on such absorption.','To either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government or count the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','Rule 35- Pension on absorption in or under a State Government: \nRule 35(1) A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45. \nRule 35(6) Where a pension scheme similar to the pension scheme under these rules exists in the State Government in which a Government servant is absorbed, he shall be entitled to exercise option either,- (a) to receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with sub-rule (1); or (b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government.'],
['Who bears the liability of proportionate pension when a Government servant exercises an option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in a State Government?','The Central Government will bear the liability of proportionate pension upon retirement.',' The State Government will bear the liability of proportionate pension upon retirement.','There will be no liability of proportionate pension borne by the Central Government upon retirement.','None of the above','There will be no liability of proportionate pension borne by the Central Government upon retirement.','Rule 35(6): Where a pension scheme similar to the pension scheme under these rules exists in the State Government in which a Government servant is absorbed, he shall be entitled to exercise option either,- \n(a) to receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with sub-rule (1); or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government. \nRule 35(7): When a Government servant is absorbed in a State Government and chooses to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government, the State Government will be responsible for paying the pension and gratuity for the entire service, including the service rendered in the Central Government, upon retirement. The Central Government will not have any liability of proportionate pension in this case.'],
['When a Government servant is absorbed in a Corporation or Company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in such Corporation or Company shall not exceed:','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from that Corporation or Company.','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant retired from Government service on the same pay which he drew on the date of absorption in that Corporation or Company','Either (a) or (b) whichever is higher','None of the above','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from that Corporation or Company.','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nA Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nThe total amount of gratuity on retirement from the Corporation, Company or Body, in respect of service rendered under the Government and the Corporation/Company/Body, should not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay from the Corporation/Company/Body.'],
['A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have ______________ from service from the date of absorption.','Resigned','Retired','Tecnically resigned','None of the above','Retired','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nA Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nThe total amount of gratuity on retirement from the Corporation, Company or Body, in respect of service rendered under the Government and the Corporation/Company/Body, should not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay from the Corporation/Company/Body.'],
['What is the date of absorption in the case of a government employee who initially joins a corporation or company or body on foreign service terms?','The date on which he actually joins that corporation or company or body','The date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the Government','The date on which he completes his foreign service tenure.','None of the above','The date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the Government','Rule 36(2): The date of absorption for a government servant who joins a corporation or company or body wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government or in or under a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government shall be: \n(i) the date on which the government servant actually joins the corporation or company or body, if he joins on immediate absorption basis. \n ii) the date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the government, if he initially joins the corporation or company or body on foreign service terms.'],
['The absorption of a Govt. Servant in or under a corporation, company or body may be permitted: \n1. In or under a Corporation or Company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government. \n2. In or under a Body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government. \n3. In joint sector undertakings under the joint control of Central/State Governments or Union territory administrations or multiple State Governments or Union territory administrations.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1 and 3 only','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension, service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nRule 36(3): The provisions of sub-rule (1) shall also apply to Central Government servants who are permitted to be absorbed in joint sector undertakings, wholly under the joint control of the Central Government and State Governments or Union territory administrations or under the joint control of two or more State Governments or Union territory administrations.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct for a Government employee joining a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption: \n1. A relieving order shall be issued in Format 4 indicating the period within which the Government servant should join. \n2. The relieving authority may extend the period if the Government servant has reasons beyond their control, which must be recorded in writing.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','2 only','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \n Rule 36(4) In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order shall be issued in the Format 5. \nRule 36(5) The relieving order shall indicate the period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body: Provided that this period may be extended by the relieving authority for reasons beyond the control of the Government servant, which shall be recorded in writing. \nRule 36(6) The period between the date of relief and the date of joining in the Corporation or Company or the Body may be regularised by grant of leave due and if no such leave is due, the period may be regularised by grant of extraordinary leave.'],
['In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, what does the relieving order issued in Format 5 indicate?','The emoluments to be received by the Government servant.','The period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body','The amount of service gratuity to be received by the Government servant','The amount of retirement gratuity to be received by the Government servant','The period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \n Rule 36(4) In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order shall be issued in the Format 5. \nRule 36(5) The relieving order shall indicate the period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body: Provided that this period may be extended by the relieving authority for reasons beyond the control of the Government servant, which shall be recorded in writing. \nRule 36(6) The period between the date of relief and the date of joining in the Corporation or Company or the Body may be regularised by grant of leave due and if no such leave is due, the period may be regularised by grant of extraordinary leave.'],
['What happens to the Government servant\'s lien in the relieving department upon absorption in the Corporation or Company or Body?','It is retained by the Government servant for 2 years from the date of absorption','It is transferred to the Corporation or Company or Body','It is terminated and all connections with the Government are severed','It is suspended until the Government servant\'s return to Government service','It is terminated and all connections with the Government are severed','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(8) No lien of the Government servant shall be retained in the relieving department and all his connections with the Government shall stand severed on his absorption in the Corporation or Company or the Body.'],
['Which of the following options is available to a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government where a similar pension scheme exists?','To receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government','To count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension','Either (a) or (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Either (a) or (b)','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension.'],
['What happens when a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government exercises an option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body?','The Government will continue to pay the pension as usual.','The Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one-time payment.','The Government will transfer the pension liability to the body.','There is no pension liability on Central Govt. in such case','The Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one-time payment.','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10) Where a Government servant is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government and exercises an option under clause (b) of sub-rule (9), the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one time payment.'],
['How is the lump sum amount of pension determined in the case of a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government?','Based on the last drawn salary of the Government servant.','Based on the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.','Based on the Contributory Provident Fund Rules (India ), 1962','Based on the number of years of service rendered by the Government servant.','Based on the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.','Rule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10): if a Government servant chooses option (b) under sub-rule (9) and is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government, the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying a lump sum as a one-time payment. \nRule 36(11): The pension liability will comprise the capitalized value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body. \nRule 36(12): The amount of the lump sum pension will be determined using the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],
['What does the pension liability comprise of for a government servant who is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government?','Only the capitalised value of pension.','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of relieving from Central Govt.','Only the capitalised value of service gratuity and retirement gratuity up to the date of relieving from Central Govt.','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body','Rule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10): if a Government servant chooses option (b) under sub-rule (9) and is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government, the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying a lump sum as a one-time payment. \nRule 36(11): The pension liability will comprise the capitalized value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body. \nRule 36(12): The amount of the lump sum pension will be determined using the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],

];